ate=2011-07-20}}</ref> elected March 11, 1876\n*[[William Smithe]] Minister of Finance and Agriculture,<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |last=Eastwood |first=T M |title=William Smithe|encyclopedia=[[Dictionary of Canadian Biography Online]] |year=1982 |url=http://www.biographi.ca/009004-119.01-e.php?&id_nbr=5834 |accessdate=2011-07-20}}</ref> acclaimed August 14, 1876\n*[[Alexander Edmund Batson Davie]], Provincial Secretary,<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |last=Lewis |first=Zane H |title=Alexander Edmund Batson Davie|encyclopedia=[[Dictionary of Canadian Biography Online]] |year=1982 |url=http://www.biographi.ca/009004-119.01-e.php?&id_nbr=5466 |accessdate=2011-07-20| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110605074514/http://www.biographi.ca/009004-119.01-e.php?&id_nbr=5466| archivedate= 5 June 2011 | url-status= live}}</ref> defeated by [[George Cowan (politician)|George Cowan]] on June 20, 1877\n\nBy-elections were held to replace members for various other reasons:<ref name=\"elections\"/>\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Electoral district\n!Member elected\n!Election date\n!Reason\n|-\n|[[Kootenay (provincial electoral district)|Kootenay]]\n|[[William Cosgrove Milby]]\n|August 24, 1876\n|A.W. Vowell named Gold Commissioner for Cassiar\n|-\n|[[Nanaimo (provincial electoral district)|Nanaimo]]\n|[[David William Gordon]]\n|January 19, 1877\n|J. Bryden resigned his seat to look after his business interests\n|-\n|[[Kootenay (provincial electoral district)|Kootenay]]\n|[[Robert Leslie Thomas Galbraith]]\n|December 20, 1877\n|death of W.C. Milby on October 26, 1877\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{British Columbia politics}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:002}}\n[[Category:Political history of British Columbia]]\n[[Category:Terms of British Columbia Parliaments]]\n[[Category:1875 establishments in British Columbia]]\n[[Category:1878 disestablishments in British Columbia]]\n", "text_old": "The '''2nd Legislative Assembly of British Columbia''' sat from 1875 to 1878. The members were elected in the [[1875 British Columbia general election|British Columbia general election]] held in September and October 1875.<ref name=\"elections\">{{cite web |url=http://www.elections.bc.ca/docs/rpt/1871\u20131986_ElectoralHistoryofBC.pdf |title=Electoral History of British Columbia, 1871\u20131986 |publisher=Elections BC |accessdate=2011-07-16 }}{{Dead link|date=April 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The government of [[George Anthony Walkem]] was defeated on a [[motion of no confidence|confidence motion]] on January 25, 1876, and [[Andrew Charles Elliott]] was asked to form a new government.<ref name=\"ormsby\"/> On March 29, 1878, a government bill to redistribute the seats in the legislature was defeated<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fNpGZ2ejpIUC&pg=PA43&lpg=PA43 |title=British Columbia's premiers in profile: the good, the bad, and the transient |last=Rayner |first=William |ISBN=1-895811-71-6 |publisher=Heritage House Publishing Co |year=2000 |page=43 |accessdate=2011-07-20}}</ref> and the assembly was dissolved on April 12, 1878.<ref name=\"ormsby\"/>\n\nThere were three sessions of the 2nd Legislature:<ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.ourroots.ca/page.aspx?id=491642 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20140812034623/http://www.ourroots.ca/page.aspx?id=491642 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2014-08-12 |title=History of British Columbia from its earliest discovery to the present time |page=546 |last=Begg |first=Alexander |year=1894 }}</ref>\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Session\n!Start\n!End\n|-\n| 1st\n| January 10, 1876\n| May 19, 1877\n|-\n| 2nd\n| February 21, 1877\n| April 18, 1877\n|-\n| 3rd\n| February 7, 1878\n| April 10, 1878\n|}\n\n[[James Trimble (Canadian politician)|James Trimble]] served as speaker.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.llbc.leg.bc.ca/public/reference/speakers.pdf |title=Speakers of the Legislative Assembly of British Columbia 1872- |publisher=BC Legislature |accessdate=2011-07-20}}</ref>\n\n=