irst=|url=https://elections.bc.ca/docs/rpt/1871-1986_ElectoralHistoryofBC.pdf|title=Electoral History of British Columbia 1871-1986|publisher=Elections British Columbia|year=1988|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\n*[[Alexander Rocke Robertson|A. Rocke Robertson]], Provincial Secretary,<ref name=\"kerr\"/> acclaimed November 28, 1871\n*[[Henry Holbrook]], Chief Commissioner of Lands and Works,<ref name=\"kerr\"/> acclaimed November 28, 1871\n*[[George Anthony Walkem|George A. Walkem]], Minister of Finance,<ref name=\"kerr\"/> acclaimed February 23, 1872\n*[[John Ash (politician)|John Ash]], Provincial Secretary,<ref>[http://www.biographi.ca/009004-119.01-e.php?&id_nbr=5347 John Ash] - Dictionary of Canadian Biography (accessed 2010-01-09).</ref> acclaimed January 11, 1873\n*[[Robert Beaven]], Chief Commissioner of Lands and Works,<ref>[http://www.biographi.ca/009004-119.01-e.php?&id_nbr=7196 Robert Beaven] - Dictionary of Canadian Biography (accessed 2010-01-09).</ref> acclaimed January 6, 1873\n*[[William James Armstrong|William Armstrong]], Minister of Finance and Agriculture,<ref name=\"mackintosh\">{{cite book |url=http://www.canadiana.org/view/32951/0377 |title=The Canadian parliamentary companion and annual register, 1877 |page=375 |year=1877 |last=Mackintosh |first=C. H |authorlink=Charles H. Mackintosh |accessdate=2011-07-16}}</ref> acclaimed March 21, 1873\n\nBy-elections were held to replace members for various other reasons:<ref name=\":0\" />\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Electoral district\n!Member elected\n!Election date\n!Reason\n|-\n|[[Cariboo (provincial electoral district)|Cariboo]]\n|[[John George Barnston]]\n|June 22, 1872\n|C. Booth appointed judge\n|-\n|[[Lillooet (electoral district)|Lillooet]]\n|[[William Saul]]\n|December 21, 1872\n|Death of A.T. Jamieson in October 1872\n|-\n|rowspan=2 |[[Victoria (British Columbia electoral district)|Victoria District]]\n|[[William Archibald Robertson]]\n|rowspan=2 |February 26, 1874\n|rowspan=2 |A. Bunster and A. de Cosmos elected to federal seats\n|-\n|[[William Fraser Tolmie]]\n|-\n|rowspan=2 |[[Lillooet (electoral district)|Lillooet]]\n|[[Thomas Basil Humphreys]]\n|rowspan=2 |November 17, 1874\n|rowspan=2 |both members resigned in a \"dispute between the two gentlemen as to which represents the popular feeling of the district\"\n|-\n|[[William Brown (British Columbia politician)|William M. Brown]]\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{British Columbia politics}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:001}}\n[[Category:Political history of British Columbia]]\n[[Category:Terms of British Columbia Parliaments]]\n[[Category:1871 establishments in British Columbia]]\n[[Category:1875 disestablishments in British Columbia]]\n", "text_old": "The '''1st Legislative Assembly of British Columbia''' sat from 1871 to 1875. The members were elected in the [[1871 British Columbia general election|British Columbia general election]] held in October 1871. [[John Foster McCreight]] was called upon to form a cabinet. In December 1872, the government was defeated on a [[motion of no confidence|confidence motion]] and [[Amor De Cosmos]] subsequently formed a new cabinet. After De Cosmos was elected to the House of Commons in February 1874, [[George Anthony Walkem|George A. Walken]] became premier.<ref name=\"kerr\">{{cite book |url=http://www.canadiana.org/view/15438/0107 |title=Biographical dictionary of well-known British Columbians with a historical sketch |page=61 |last=Kerr |first=John Blaine |year=1890 |accessdate=2011-07-16}}</ref>\n\nThere were four sessions of the 1st Legislature:<ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.ourroots.ca/page.aspx?id=491642 |title=History of British Columbia from its earliest discovery to the present time |page=546 |last=Begg |first=Alexander |year=1894 |access-date=2014-08-11 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20140812034623/http://www.ourroots.ca/page.aspx?id=491642 |archive-date=2014-08-12 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Session\n!Start\n!End\n|-\n|