ez]] {{goal|6}}\n|goals2     = [[Edward Linskens|Linskens]] {{goal|19}}<br>Van Aerle{{yel|55}}<br>[[Wim Kieft|Kieft]]{{yel|78}}\n|stadium    = [[Santiago Bernab\u00e9u Stadium]]\n|location   = [[Madrid]]\n|attendance =\n|referee    =\n|result     = D\n|stack      = Y\n}}\n{{footballbox collapsible\n|round      = \n|date       = 20 April 1988\n|time       = 19:30 [[Central European Time|CET]]\n|team1      = [[PSV Eindhoven|PSV]] {{flagicon|NED}}\n|score      = 0\u20130\n|aggregatescore = 1[[Away goals rule|a]] \u20131\n|report     = [http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=1987/matches/round=24/match=4083/postmatch/lineups/index.html Report] \n|team2      = {{flagicon|ESP}} [[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]]\n|goals1     = Vanenburg{{yel|75}}\n|goals2     = Chendo{{yel|75}}\n|stadium    = [[Philips Stadion]]\n|location   = [[Eindhoven]]\n|attendance =\n|referee    =\n|result     = D\n}}\n\n== Statistics ==\n=== Squad statistics ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:90%;width:60%;float:left;text-align:center;\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" | competition\n! rowspan=\"2\" | points\n! colspan=\"6\" | total\n! rowspan=\"2\" | [[goal diference|DR]]\n|-\n! {{Descrizione comando|G|Games played}}\n! {{Descrizione comando|V|Games won}}\n! {{Descrizione comando|N|Games drawed}}\n! {{Descrizione comando|P|Games lost}}\n! {{Descrizione comando|Gf|Goal scored}}\n! {{Descrizione comando|Gs|Goal against}}\n|-\n| [[La Liga]] || '''56''' || 34 || 26 || 4 || 4 || 83 || 33 || +50\n|-\n| [[Copa del Rey]]\n| - || 6 || 4 || 1 || 1 || 14 || 6 || +8\n|-\n| [[UEFA Cup]]\n| - || 12 || 6 || 1 || 5 || 26 || 16 || +10\n|-\n! Total || || 52 || 36 || 6 || 10 || 113 || 55 || +58\n|}\n{{clear}}\n\n=== Players statistics ===\n<ref>[http://www.bdfutbol.com/en/t/t1985-862.html ''Real Madrid temporada 1985-86''] su [http://www.bdfutbol.com/ bdfutbol.com]</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:90%;width:70%;float:left;text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Player\n! colspan=\"4\" | La Liga\n|-\n! Matches\n! Goals\n! Yellow\n! Sent off\n|-\n| Agust\u00edn || 12 ||  ||  || \n|-\n| [[Emilio Butrague\u00f1o|Butrague\u00f1o]] || 31 || 10 ||  || \n|-\n| Camacho || 29 ||  || 3 || \n|-\n| Chendo || 30 ||  || 3 || \n|-\n| Cholo || 8 || 3 || 1 || \n|-\n| Gallego || 31 || 2 || 3 || \n|-\n| Gordillo || 22 || 1 ||  || \n|-\n| [[Juanito (footballer, born 1954)|Juanito]] || 28 || 4 || 3 || \n|-\n| Maceda || 28 || 5 || 6 || \n|-\n| Mart\u00edn V\u00e1zquez || 17 || 3 ||  || \n|-\n| M\u00edchel || 31 || 7 || 3 || \n|-\n| Otxotorena || 28 ||  || 1 || \n|-\n| Rodr\u00edguez || 12 ||  ||  || \n|-\n| Salguero || 14 || 1 || 1 || \n|-\n| [[Hugo S\u00e1nchez]] || 41 || 34 || 2 || 1\n|-\n| [[Manolo Sanch\u00eds]] || 29 || 1 || 5 || \n|-\n| San Jos\u00e9 || 6 ||  ||  || \n|-\n| Santillana || 27 || 4 || 1 || \n|-\n| Solana || 4 || 2 ||  || \n|-\n| [[Jorge Valdano]] || 32 || 16 || 3 || \n|}{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Real Madrid CF seasons}}\n{{1987\u201388 in Spanish football}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1987-88 Real Madrid CF season}}\n[[Category:Real Madrid CF seasons]]\n[[Category:Spanish football clubs 1987\u201388 season|Real Madrid CF]]\n[[Category:Spanish football championship-winning seasons]]\n", "name_user": "Bobly", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMatches", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1987%E2%80%9388_Real_Madrid_CF_season"}
{"title_page": "Jimmy Davis (footballer)", "text_new": "{{Other people|James Davis}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2012}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n|           name = Jimmy Davis\n|          image = \n|        caption = \n|       fullname = James Roger William Davis<ref name=\"hugman\">{{Hugman|4851|accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n|     birth_date = {{birth date|1982|2|6|df=y}}<ref name=\"hugman\"/>\n|    birth_place = [[Bromsgrove]], England<ref name=\"bromsgrove\">{{cite book|last1=Butler |first1=Cliff |last2=Ponting |first2=Ivan |title=Manchester United Official Yearbook 2000: The Definitive Guide to the 1999\u22122000 Season |page=164 |publisher=Carlton Books Limited |date=June 2000 |url=https://archive.org/details/manchesterunited0000unse/page/164/ |isbn=978-0-2339978-3-4 |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n|     death_date = {{death date and age|2003|8|9|1982|2|6|df=y}}\n|    death_place = [[Oxfordshire]], England\n|         height = {{height|m=1.73}}<ref name=\"bromsgrove\"/><ref name=\"soccerbase\">{{cite web|url=https://www.soccerbase.com/players/player.sd?player_id=23849 |url-status=live |title=Jimmy Davis |work=Soccerbase |publisher=Centurycomm Ltd |accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref>\n|       position = [[Midfielder#Winger|Winger]]<ref name=\"hugman\"/><br/>[[Forward (association football)|Forward]]<ref name=\"bromsgrove\"/>\n|    youthyears1 = 1998\u20131999 |youthclubs1 = [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]]\n|         years1 = 1999\u20132003 |clubs1 = [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]]  |caps1 = 0  |goals1 = 0\n|         years2 = 2001      |clubs2 = \u2192 [[Royal Antwerp F.C.|Royal Antwerp]] (loan) |caps2 = 7  |goals2 = 0\n|         years3 = 2002      |clubs3 = \u2192 [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]] (loan)   |caps3 = 13 |goals3 = 2\n|         years4 = 2003      |clubs4 = \u2192 [[Watford F.C.|Watford]] (loan)             |caps4 = 0  |goals4 = 0\n|      totalcaps = 20        | totalgoals = 2\n| nationalyears1 = 1999      | nationalteam1 = [[England national under-16 football team|England U16]] | nationalcaps1 = 1 | nationalgoals1 = 0\n| nationalyears2 = 2000      | nationalteam2 = [[England national under-18 football team|England U18]] | nationalcaps2 = 1 | nationalgoals2 = 0\n| nationalyears3 = 2001\u20132002 | nationalteam3 = [[England national under-20 football team|England U20]] | nationalcaps3 = 7 | nationalgoals3 = 3\n}}\n'''James Roger William Davis''' (6 February 1982 \u2013 9 August 2003) was a [[association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Forward (association football)|forward]]. He signed for [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] as a youth trainee in July 1999 and the following month he signed professional terms with the club. He played numerous times for the youth and [[Manchester United F.C. Reserves and Academy|reserve]] sides at United and was part of the team that won the [[Manchester Senior Cup]] in  May 2000. He had a short spell on [[Loan (sports)|loan]] at Belgian club [[Royal Antwerp F.C.|Royal Antwerp]] in 2001 before returning to United and making his senior debut in the [[EFL Cup|League Cup]] tie against [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] during the [[2001\u201302 Manchester United F.C. season|2001\u201302 season]]. He was an England youth international as he progressed from the [[England national under-16 football team|under-16s]] to the [[England national under-20 football team|under-20s]] during his time at [[Old Trafford]].\n\nDavis spent three months on loan with [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]] club [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]] in 2002 and scored three goals in 15 appearances. He was a mainstay in the reserves on his return to United; his only involvement with the first team after returning was as an unused [[Substitute (association football)|substitute]] in a league game against [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]]  and a [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] second group stage match against [[Deportivo de La Coru\u00f1a]]. In July 2003, he joined [[Football League First Division|First Division]] club [[Watford F.C.|Watford]] on season-long loan. \n\nDavis was killed on the morning on 9 August 2003 when his car was in a collision with a [[Truck|lorry]] whilst travelling southbound on the [[M40 motorway|M40]] in [[Oxfordshire]]. He was due to make his debut for Watford against [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]] that afternoon. An [[Inquests in England and Wales|inquest]] determined he was travelling at around 120mph at the time of the incident, and was twice the legal [[Driving under the influence#United Kingdom|drink-drive limit]].<ref name=\"inquest\"/>\n\n==Early life==\nDavis was born in [[Bromsgrove]], Worcestershire.<ref name=\"bromsgrove\"/> He lived in [[Redditch]] and attended Marlfield Farm First School<ref name=\"earlyyears\">{{cite web|url=http://www.angelfire.com/pro/jimmydavis/Earlyyears.html |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040913183908/http://www.angelfire.com/pro/jimmydavis/Earlyyears.html |archivedate=13 September 2004 |title=Jimmy Davis \u2212 Early Years |publisher=Jimmy Davis Memorial Website |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> and later [[RSA Academy Arrow Vale|Arrow Vale High School]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/hereford/worcs/3170367.stm |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160416083640/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/england/hereford/worcs/3170367.stm |archivedate=16 April 2016 |title=Football stars united in grief |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=21 August 2003 |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> He played football from an early age, firstly with a [[Cub Scout#United Kingdom|Cub's]] team, and then with junior sides of local clubs [[Feckenham F.C.|Feckenham]] and [[Knowle F.C.|Knowle]].<ref name=\"earlyyears\"/>\n\n==Club career==\n\n===Manchester United===\nDavis signed as a youth trainee at [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] in July 1999.<ref name=\"bromsgrove\"/> He played in the Jersey Tournament in August 1999; he took part in the win versus [[Rangers F.C. Under-20s and Academy|Rangers]]<ref>{{cite book|last1=Butler |first1=Cliff |last2=Ponting |first2=Ivan |title=Manchester United Official Yearbook 2000: The Definitive Guide to the 1999\u22122000 Season |page=186 |publisher=Carlton Books Limited |date=June 2000 |url=https://archive.org/details/manchesterunited0000unse/page/186/ |isbn=978-0-2339978-3-4 |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> and the defeat against [[S.L. Benfica Juniors|Benfica]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Butler |first1=Cliff |last2=Ponting |first2=Ivan |title=Manchester United Official Yearbook 2000: The Definitive Guide to the 1999\u22122000 Season |page=187 |publisher=Carlton Books Limited |date=June 2000 |url=https://archive.org/details/manchesterunited0000unse/page/187/ |isbn=978-0-2339978-3-4 |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> At the end of August he signed a professional contract with United.<ref name=\"bromsgrove\"/> On 25 September, Davis scored a [[Hat-trick#Association football|hat-trick]] in the [[Premier Academy League|FA Premier Academy League]] under-19 match against [[Stoke City F.C. Under-23s and Academy|Stoke City]].<ref name=\"redstat\">{{cite web|url=http://www.redstat.co.uk/?PlayerNo=393 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://archive.today/mCDBU |archivedate=20 April 2020 |title=Jimmy Davis |work=redStat.co.uk |publisher=redStat \u2212 Manchester United Statistics |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> United won the game 5\u22120.<ref name=\"redstat\"/> He played in the 2\u22121 defeat against [[Nottingham Forest F.C. Under-23s, Under-18s and Academy|Nottingham Forest]] in the [[FA Youth Cup]] third round at [[Gigg Lane]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Butler |first1=Cliff |last2=Ponting |first2=Ivan |title=Manchester United Official Yearbook 2000: The Definitive Guide to the 1999\u22122000 Season |page=197 |publisher=Carlton Books Limited |date=June 2000 |url=https://archive.org/details/manchesterunited0000unse/page/197/ |isbn=978-0-2339978-3-4 |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> He started to feature for the [[Manchester United F.C. Reserves and Academy|reserves]] more regularly at the beginning on 2000,<ref name=\"redstat\"/> and he scored in the [[Premier Reserve League]] match against [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] in February.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Butler |first1=Cliff |last2=Ponting |first2=Ivan |title=Manchester United Official Yearbook 2000: The Definitive Guide to the 1999\u22122000 Season |page=174 |publisher=Carlton Books Limited |date=June 2000 |url=https://archive.org/details/manchesterunited0000unse/page/174/ |isbn=978-0-2339978-3-4 |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> On 2 May, he played in the [[Manchester Senior Cup]] final at [[Boundary Park]]; he replaced [[Darren Fletcher]] as United won 2\u22120 against [[Oldham Athletic A.F.C.|Oldham Athletic]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Butler |first1=Cliff |last2=Ponting |first2=Ivan |title=Manchester United Official Yearbook 2000: The Definitive Guide to the 1999\u22122000 Season |page=177 |publisher=Carlton Books Limited |date=June 2000 |url=https://archive.org/details/manchesterunited0000unse/page/177/ |isbn=978-0-2339978-3-4 |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nDavis featured in the [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]] Centenary Youth Tournament in August 2000; he played in four games and scored against [[FC Bayern Munich Junior Team|Bayern Munich]] and [[FC Spartak Moscow|Spartak Moscow]].<ref name=\"redstat\"/> On 28 September, he scored as United beat [[Bury F.C.|Bury]] 8\u22121 in the Manchester Senior Cup.<ref name=\"redstat\"/> His next goal came in the return game with Bury at the end of November.<ref name=\"redstat\"/> He concluded his season by taking part in a second successive Manchester Senior Cup final.<ref name=\"redstat\"/> He started the game against [[Manchester City F.C. EDS and Academy|Manchester City]] but United lost 4\u22121 at [[Old Trafford]].<ref name=\"redstat\"/>\n\n====Royal Antwerp (loan)====\nIn January 2001, Davis joined [[Belgian First Division A|Belgian Pro League]] club [[Royal Antwerp F.C.|Royal Antwerp]] on loan until the end of the season.<ref name=\"redstat\"/> United had a relationship with Antwerp at the time that would see young players being loaned to Belgian club to gain first team experience.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mufclatest.com/whatever-happened-to-royal-antwerp-the-feeder-club-conundrum/ |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190918180653/http://mufclatest.com/whatever-happened-to-royal-antwerp-the-feeder-club-conundrum/ |archivedate=18 September 2019 |title=Whatever happened to Royal Antwerp? The feeder club conundrum |first=Andrew |last=Bruce |publisher=MUFC Latest |date=1 June 2018 |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> However, he only made seven appearances for Antwerp and didn't manage to score any goals.<ref name=\"redstat\"/>\n\nDavis made a positive start to the [[2001\u201302 Manchester United F.C. season|2001\u201302 season]]; he scored a hat-trick for the reserves against [[Newcastle Town F.C.|Newcastle Town]] at the end of September 2001, and then scored two more against [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C. Academy|Sheffield Wednesday]] on 1 November.<ref name=\"redstat\"/> Four days later, he made his senior debut in the [[EFL Cup|League Cup]] tie against [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] at [[Arsenal Stadium|Highbury]].<ref name=\"redstat\"/><ref name=\"debutarse\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/worthington_cup/1637817.stm |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306220908/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/worthington_cup/1637817.stm |archivedate=6 March 2016 |title=Arsenal win battle of reserves |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=5 November 2001 |accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref> He played the full game but United lost the [[2001\u201302 Football League Cup#Third round|third round]] match 4\u20130.<ref name=\"debutarse\"/> Back in the reserves, Davis continued to impress and scored four goals in six games between December and February 2002.<ref name=\"redstat\"/> He scored another hat-trick in the friendly against [[Drumchapel Amateur F.C.|Drumchapel Amateurs]] in March as United ran out 8\u22120 winners.<ref name=\"redstat\"/> Overall, he made 18 league appearances and scored six goals as United won the Premier Reserve League North.<ref name=\"redstat\"/>\n\n====Swindon Town (loan)====\nDavis joined [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]] club [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]] on a three-month loan deal in August 2002.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.swindontownfc.co.uk/today/view/breaking_news_detail/0,,10341~253023,00.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020818141949/http://www.swindontownfc.co.uk:80/today/view/breaking_news_detail/0,,10341~253023,00.html |archivedate=18 August 2002 |title=Jimmy Davis Signs Three-Month Contract |work=SwindonTownFC.co.uk |publisher=Swindon Town Football Club |date=9 August 2002 |accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref> On 10 August, he made his debut in the league game against [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]] when he replaced [[Danny Invincibile]] in the 84th minute of the 3\u22121 win.<ref name=\"season0203\">{{soccerbase season|23849|2002|accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.swindontownfc.co.uk/stats/view/postmatch_analysis/0,,10341~253510,00.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020818142232/http://www.swindontownfc.co.uk:80/stats/view/postmatch_analysis/0,,10341~253510,00.html |archivedate=18 August 2002 |title=Swindon Town 3 Barnsley 1 |work=SwindonTownFC.co.uk |publisher=Swindon Town Football Club |date=10 August 2002 |accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref> A week later he made his full debut in the goalless draw with [[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]] at [[Bloomfield Road]].<ref name=\"season0203\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.swindontownfc.co.uk/stats/view/postmatch_analysis/0,,10341~257798,00.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020822134048/http://www.swindontownfc.co.uk:80/stats/view/postmatch_analysis/0,,10341~257798,00.html |archivedate=22 August 2002 |title=Blackpool 0 Swindon Town 0 |work=SwindonTownFC.co.uk |publisher=Swindon Town Football Club |date=17 August 2002 |accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref> He scored his first goal for Swindon in the defeat against [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]] at the end of August.<ref name=\"season0203\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_2/2199507.stm |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040509141540/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_2/2199507.stm |archivedate=9 May 2004 |title=Brentford 3\u22121 Swindon |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=26 August 2002 |accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref> On 22 October, Davis scored in the [[EFL Trophy|Football League Trophy]] tie against [[Southend United F.C.|Southend United]]; he beat three players on the edge of the area before scoring as Town went on to win 6\u22121 in the [[2002\u201303 Football League Trophy#First round|first round]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/2344845.stm |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200201142808/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/2344845.stm |archivedate=1 February 2020 |title=Swindon 6\u22121 Southend |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=22 October 2002 |accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref> He scored again on 2 November against [[Wycombe Wanderers F.C.|Wycombe Wanderers]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_2/2363985.stm |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040523212155/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_2/2363985.stm |archivedate=23 May 2004 |title=Wycombe 2\u22123 Southend |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=2 November 2002 |accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref> and a week later he played in the 1\u22121 draw against [[Tranmere Rovers F.C.|Tranmere Rovers]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_2/2388065.stm |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040712025451/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_2/2388065.stm |archivedate=12 July 2004 |title=Swindon 1\u22121 Tranmere |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=9 November 2002 |accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref> the latter being his final appearance for Swindon.<ref name=\"season0203\"/> Town manager [[Andy King (footballer, born 1956)|Andy King]] was keen to keep Davis on loan at the club but United manager [[Alex Ferguson]] refused to extend the deal and Davis returned to Old Trafford following the Tranmere game.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.gazetteandherald.co.uk/news/7334954.jims-a-goner/ |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200421115151/https://www.gazetteandherald.co.uk/news/7334954.jims-a-goner/ |archivedate=21 April 2020 |title=Jim's a Goner |work=Gazette & Herald |publisher=Newsquest Media Group Ltd |date=8 November 2002 |accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref> Overall, he made 15 appearances for Swindon and scored three goals.<ref name=\"season0203\"/>\n\nUpon returning to United, Davis was involved in the first team when he was an unused substitute in the [[Premier League]] match at [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] on 17 November.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/2430783.stm |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160319203642/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/eng_prem/2430783.stm |archivedate=19 March 2016 |title=Defoe denies Man Utd |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=17 November 2002 |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> He was again an unused substitute in their [[UEFA Champions League]] second group stage match away to [[Deportivo La Coruna]] on 18 March 2003.<ref>{{cite news |title=Deportivo see off Man Utd |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/champions_league/2856429.stm |website=BBC Sport |date=18 March 2003 |accessdate=20 April 2020 }}</ref> He joined [[Watford F.C.|Watford]] on a season-long loan on 8 July 2003.<ref>{{cite news |title=Watford lure Man Utd fledgling |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/w/watford/3054232.stm |website=BBC Sport |date=8 July 2003 |accessdate=20 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\n==International career==\n===Under-16===\nDavis represented [[England national under-16 football team|England]] at the [[1999 UEFA European Under-16 Championship]]. On 2 May 1999, he featured in the quarter final defeat against host nation [[Czech Republic national under-17 football team|Czech Republic]]; he replaced [[Jamie McMaster]] in the 86th minute as England lost 1\u22120 [[Overtime (sports)#Association football|after extra time]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://nv.fotbal.cz/en-national-teams/national-team-u-16/statistics/viewstat2.asp?page=/nat/16/1998/match15.asp |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180722011401/http://nv.fotbal.cz/en-national-teams/national-team-u-16/statistics/viewstat2.asp?page=/nat/16/1998/match15.asp |archivedate=22 July 2018 |title=Z\u00e1pis o utk\u00e1n\u00ed \u010d. 86 |work=Fotbal.cz |publisher=Fotbalov\u00e9 asociace \u010cesk\u00e9 republiky |language=Czech |date=2 May 1999 |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Under-18===\nDavis played for the [[England national under-18 football team|England under-18s]] in the win against [[Belgium national under-18 football team|Belgium]] in November 2000.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.dorsetecho.co.uk/news/5407330.defoe-given-half-a-game/ |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420123850/https://www.dorsetecho.co.uk/news/5407330.defoe-given-half-a-game/ |archivedate=20 April 2020 |title=Defoe given half a game |first= |last= |work=Dorset Echo |publisher=Newsquest Media Group Ltd |date=18 November 2000 |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Under-20===\nDavis made his debut for the [[England national under-20 football team|England under-20s]] in November 2001; he started the win against [[Portugal national under-20 football team|Portugal]] at [[St Mary's Stadium]] before being replaced by [[Andrew Johnson (footballer, born 1981)|Andrew Johnson]].<ref name=\"engonline\">{{cite web|url=http://www.englandfootballonline.com/MatchRsl/MatchRslTmU20.html |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229151245/http://www.englandfootballonline.com/MatchRsl/MatchRslTmU20.html |archivedate=29 February 2020 |title=England's Matches the under 20's |work=EnglandFootballOnline.com |publisher=England Football Online \u2212 Chris Goodwin & Glen Isherwood |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> On 13 March 2002, he scored two goals in the win against [[Finland national under-20 football team|Finland]] at the [[University of Bolton Stadium|Reebok Stadium]].<ref name=\"engonline\"/> He was a part of the squad that participated in the [[Toulon Tournament]] in May 2002;<ref name=\"espoirs\">{{cite web|url=https://festival-foot-espoirs.com/festival/archives/palmares.php?annee=2002 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190914203846/https://festival-foot-espoirs.com/festival/archives/palmares.php?annee=2002 |archivedate=14 September 2019 |title=30\u00c8 Festival International Espoirs |work=Festival-Foot-Espoirs.com |publisher=Festival International Espoirs |language=French |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> he featured in four games, scoring the winning goal in the group game against Portugal,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thefa.com/England/U20s/NewsAndFeatures/Postings/2002/05/11456.htm |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040313204835/http://www.thefa.com:80/England/U20s/NewsAndFeatures/Postings/2002/05/11456.htm |archivedate=13 March 2004 |title=Toulon: Davis on cue to seal victory |first=Lawrie |last=Madden |work=TheFA.com |publisher=The Football Association |date=13 May 2002 |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> as England finished in fourth place.<ref name=\"engonline\"/><ref name=\"espoirs\"/> He received the \"Le joueur le + courtois\" award, translated as being the most courteous player in the tournament.<ref name=\"espoirs\"/> These were his last appearances for the U20s. Overall, Davis earned seven caps and scored three goals.<ref name=\"engonline\"/>\n\n==Death==\nDavis was killed in a car crash on the [[M40 motorway]] in the early hours of 9 August 2003. He crashed his [[BMW]] into a truck and was pronounced dead at the scene. The truck driver suffered minor injuries. The accident occurred just hours before Watford were due to open their season with a match against [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]]. The Watford board of directors announced later that morning that the match was postponed due to \"tragic circumstances beyond their control\", though they did not announce Davis' death for another few hours. His funeral took place at Redditch Crematorium, with the Manchester United team in attendance.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.sky.com/skynews/article/0,,30100-12740453,00.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20110522070822/http://news.sky.com/skynews/article/0,,30100-12740453,00.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=22 May 2011 |title=Stars Pay Respect To Jimmy Davis |publisher=[[Sky News]] |date=23 August 2003 |accessdate=11 February 2008 }}</ref>\n\nThe subsequent [[inquest]] reported that Davis was more than twice over the legal drink-drive limit and it was believed that he had been driving at speeds of up to 120&nbsp;mph when losing control of his car when he fell asleep at the wheel.<ref name=\"inquest\">{{cite news | url=http://www.manchesteronline.co.uk/news/s/83/83016_crash_death_footballer_twice_drink_drive_limit.html | title=Crash death footballer twice drink drive limit | publisher=[[Manchester Evening News]] | date=3 March 2004 | accessdate=1 July 2007}}</ref> The inquest returned a verdict of accidental death.<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/manchester/3529553.stm | title=Under-21 United star over limit | work=BBC News | date=3 March 2004 | accessdate=6 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nA few days after his death, Swindon dedicated their 4\u20130 win over [[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]] to the young player, with Davis's mother making a speech in front of the Swindon fans before the kick-off. Additionally, Swindon Town took part in a memorial match with his local club [[Redditch United F.C.|Redditch United]]; Swindon won 2\u20131 with [[Sam Parkin]] scoring the goals. Manchester United paid tribute to him during their [[2003 FA Community Shield]] victory against [[Arsenal FC|Arsenal]], with both teams wearing black armbands during the match. United also paid tribute to him after their victory in the [[2004 FA Cup Final]], when after the final whistle and before the presentation they changed into shirts printed with Davis's name and squad number, 36, on the back.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/fa_cup/3739335.stm | title=Players remember Davis | publisher=[[BBC]] | date=22 May 2004 | accessdate=1 July 2007}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n;Specific\n{{reflist}}\n\n;General\n*[https://www.theguardian.com/football/2013/aug/05/jimmy-davis-danny-webber-united-watford \"'Jimmy was dead, when as far as I was concerned, he was still in bed'\"], ''[[The Guardian]]'', 5 August 2013\n\n==External links==\n* {{soccerbase}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20051207155002/http://www.manutd.com/bio/bio.sps?iBiographyID=1636 Jimmy Davis] at ManUtd.com\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Davis, Jimmy}}\n[[Category:1982 births]]\n[[Category:2003 deaths]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Bromsgrove]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football wingers]]\n[[Category:Manchester United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Royal Antwerp F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Swindon Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Watford F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Belgian First Division A players]]\n[[Category:English expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Belgium]]\n[[Category:Road incident deaths in England]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other people|James Davis}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2012}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n|           name = Jimmy Davis\n|          image = \n|        caption = \n|       fullname = James Roger William Davis<ref name=\"hugman\">{{Hugman|4851|accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n|     birth_date = {{birth date|1982|2|6|df=y}}<ref name=\"hugman\"/>\n|    birth_place = [[Bromsgrove]], England<ref name=\"bromsgrove\">{{cite book|last1=Butler |first1=Cliff |last2=Ponting |first2=Ivan |title=Manchester United Official Yearbook 2000: The Definitive Guide to the 1999\u22122000 Season |page=164 |publisher=Carlton Books Limited |date=June 2000 |url=https://archive.org/details/manchesterunited0000unse/page/164/ |isbn=978-0-2339978-3-4 |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n|     death_date = {{death date and age|2003|8|9|1982|2|6|df=y}}\n|    death_place = [[Oxfordshire]], England\n|         height = {{height|m=1.73}}<ref name=\"bromsgrove\"/><ref name=\"soccerbase\">{{cite web|url=https://www.soccerbase.com/players/player.sd?player_id=23849 |url-status=live |title=Jimmy Davis |work=Soccerbase |publisher=Centurycomm Ltd |accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref>\n|       position = [[Midfielder#Winger|Winger]]<ref name=\"hugman\"/><br/>[[Forward (association football)|Forward]]<ref name=\"bromsgrove\"/>\n|    youthyears1 = 1998\u20131999 |youthclubs1 = [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]]\n|         years1 = 1999\u20132003 |clubs1 = [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]]  |caps1 = 0  |goals1 = 0\n|         years2 = 2001      |clubs2 = \u2192 [[Royal Antwerp F.C.|Royal Antwerp]] (loan) |caps2 = 7  |goals2 = 0\n|         years3 = 2002      |clubs3 = \u2192 [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]] (loan)   |caps3 = 13 |goals3 = 2\n|         years4 = 2003      |clubs4 = \u2192 [[Watford F.C.|Watford]] (loan)             |caps4 = 0  |goals4 = 0\n|      totalcaps = 20        | totalgoals = 2\n| nationalyears1 = 1999      | nationalteam1 = [[England national under-16 football team|England U16]] | nationalcaps1 = 1 | nationalgoals1 = 0\n| nationalyears2 = 2000      | nationalteam2 = [[England national under-18 football team|England U18]] | nationalcaps2 = 1 | nationalgoals2 = 0\n| nationalyears3 = 2001\u20132002 | nationalteam3 = [[England national under-20 football team|England U20]] | nationalcaps3 = 7 | nationalgoals3 = 3\n}}\n'''James Roger William Davis''' (6 February 1982 \u2013 9 August 2003) was a [[association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Forward (association football)|forward]]. He signed for [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] as a youth trainee in July 1999 and the following month he signed professional terms with the club. He played numerous times for the youth and [[Manchester United F.C. Reserves and Academy|reserve]] sides at United and was part of the team that won the [[Manchester Senior Cup]] in  May 2000. He had a short spell on [[Loan (sports)|loan]] at Belgian club [[Royal Antwerp F.C.|Royal Antwerp]] in 2001 before returning to United and making his senior debut in the [[EFL Cup|League Cup]] tie against [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] during the [[2001\u201302 Manchester United F.C. season|2001\u201302 season]]. He was an England youth international as he progressed from the [[England national under-16 football team|under-16s]] to the [[England national under-20 football team|under-20s]] during his time at [[Old Trafford]].\n\nDavis spent three months on loan with [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]] club [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]] in 2002 and scored three goals in 15 appearances. He was a mainstay in the reserves on his return to United; his only involvement with the first team after returning was as an unused [[Substitute (association football)|substitute]] in a league game against [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]]  and a [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] second group stage match against [[Deportivo de La Coru\u00f1a]]. In July 2003, he joined [[Football League First Division|First Division]] club [[Watford F.C.|Watford]] on season-long loan. \n\nDavis was killed on the morning on 9 August 2003 when his car was in a collision with a [[Truck|lorry]] whilst travelling southbound on the [[M40 motorway|M40]] in [[Oxfordshire]]. He was due to make his debut for Watford against [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]] that afternoon. An [[Inquests in England and Wales|inquest]] determined he was travelling at around 120mph at the time of the incident, and was twice the legal [[Driving under the influence#United Kingdom|drink-drive limit]].<ref name=\"inquest\"/>\n\n==Early life==\nDavis was born in [[Bromsgrove]], Worcestershire.<ref name=\"bromsgrove\"/> He lived in [[Redditch]] and attended Marlfield Farm First School<ref name=\"earlyyears\">{{cite web|url=http://www.angelfire.com/pro/jimmydavis/Earlyyears.html |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040913183908/http://www.angelfire.com/pro/jimmydavis/Earlyyears.html |archivedate=13 September 2004 |title=Jimmy Davis \u2212 Early Years |publisher=Jimmy Davis Memorial Website |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> and later [[RSA Academy Arrow Vale|Arrow Vale High School]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/hereford/worcs/3170367.stm |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160416083640/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/england/hereford/worcs/3170367.stm |archivedate=16 April 2016 |title=Football stars united in grief |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=21 August 2003 |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> He played football from an early age, firstly with a [[Cub Scout#United Kingdom|Cub's]] team, and then with junior sides of local clubs [[Feckenham F.C.|Feckenham]] and [[Knowle F.C.|Knowle]].<ref name=\"earlyyears\"/>\n\n==Club career==\n\n===Manchester United===\nDavis signed as a youth trainee at [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] in July 1999.<ref name=\"bromsgrove\"/> He played in the Jersey Tournament in August 1999; he took part in the win versus [[Rangers F.C. Under-20s and Academy|Rangers]]<ref>{{cite book|last1=Butler |first1=Cliff |last2=Ponting |first2=Ivan |title=Manchester United Official Yearbook 2000: The Definitive Guide to the 1999\u22122000 Season |page=186 |publisher=Carlton Books Limited |date=June 2000 |url=https://archive.org/details/manchesterunited0000unse/page/186/ |isbn=978-0-2339978-3-4 |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> and the defeat against [[S.L. Benfica Juniors|Benfica]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Butler |first1=Cliff |last2=Ponting |first2=Ivan |title=Manchester United Official Yearbook 2000: The Definitive Guide to the 1999\u22122000 Season |page=187 |publisher=Carlton Books Limited |date=June 2000 |url=https://archive.org/details/manchesterunited0000unse/page/187/ |isbn=978-0-2339978-3-4 |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> At the end of August he signed a professional contract with United.<ref name=\"bromsgrove\"/> On 25 September, Davis scored a [[Hat-trick#Association football|hat-trick]] in the [[Premier Academy League|FA Premier Academy League]] under-19 match against [[Stoke City F.C. Under-23s and Academy|Stoke City]].<ref name=\"redstat\">{{cite web|url=http://www.redstat.co.uk/?PlayerNo=393 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://archive.today/mCDBU |archivedate=20 April 2020 |title=Jimmy Davis |work=redStat.co.uk |publisher=redStat \u2212 Manchester United Statistics |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> United won the game 5\u22120.<ref name=\"redstat\"/> He played in the 2\u22121 defeat against [[Nottingham Forest F.C. Under-23s, Under-18s and Academy|Nottingham Forest]] in the [[FA Youth Cup]] third round at [[Gigg Lane]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Butler |first1=Cliff |last2=Ponting |first2=Ivan |title=Manchester United Official Yearbook 2000: The Definitive Guide to the 1999\u22122000 Season |page=197 |publisher=Carlton Books Limited |date=June 2000 |url=https://archive.org/details/manchesterunited0000unse/page/197/ |isbn=978-0-2339978-3-4 |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> He started to feature for the [[Manchester United F.C. Reserves and Academy|reserves]] more regularly at the beginning on 2000,<ref name=\"redstat\"/> and he scored in the [[Premier Reserve League]] match against [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] in February.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Butler |first1=Cliff |last2=Ponting |first2=Ivan |title=Manchester United Official Yearbook 2000: The Definitive Guide to the 1999\u22122000 Season |page=174 |publisher=Carlton Books Limited |date=June 2000 |url=https://archive.org/details/manchesterunited0000unse/page/174/ |isbn=978-0-2339978-3-4 |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> On 2 May, he played in the [[Manchester Senior Cup]] final at [[Boundary Park]]; he replaced [[Darren Fletcher]] as United won 2\u22120 against [[Oldham Athletic A.F.C.|Oldham Athletic]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Butler |first1=Cliff |last2=Ponting |first2=Ivan |title=Manchester United Official Yearbook 2000: The Definitive Guide to the 1999\u22122000 Season |page=177 |publisher=Carlton Books Limited |date=June 2000 |url=https://archive.org/details/manchesterunited0000unse/page/177/ |isbn=978-0-2339978-3-4 |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nDavis featured in the [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]] Centenary Youth Tournament in August 2000; he played in four games and scored against [[FC Bayern Munich Junior Team|Bayern Munich]] and [[FC Spartak Moscow|Spartak Moscow]].<ref name=\"redstat\"/> On 28 September, he scored as United beat [[Bury F.C.|Bury]] 8\u22121 in the Manchester Senior Cup.<ref name=\"redstat\"/> His next goal came in the return game with Bury at the end of November.<ref name=\"redstat\"/> He concluded his season by taking part in a second successive Manchester Senior Cup final.<ref name=\"redstat\"/> He started the game against [[Manchester City F.C. EDS and Academy|Manchester City]] but United lost 4\u22121 at [[Old Trafford]].<ref name=\"redstat\"/>\n\n====Royal Antwerp (loan)====\nIn January 2001, Davis joined [[Belgian First Division A|Belgian Pro League]] club [[Royal Antwerp F.C.|Royal Antwerp]] on loan until the end of the season.<ref name=\"redstat\"/> United had a relationship with Antwerp at the time that would see young players being loaned to Belgian club to gain first team experience.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mufclatest.com/whatever-happened-to-royal-antwerp-the-feeder-club-conundrum/ |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190918180653/http://mufclatest.com/whatever-happened-to-royal-antwerp-the-feeder-club-conundrum/ |archivedate=18 September 2019 |title=Whatever happened to Royal Antwerp? The feeder club conundrum |first=Andrew |last=Bruce |publisher=MUFC Latest |date=1 June 2018 |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> However, he only made seven appearances for Antwerp and didn't manage to score any goals.<ref name=\"redstat\"/>\n\nDavis made a positive start to the [[2001\u201302 Manchester United F.C. season|2001\u201302 season]]; he scored a hat-trick for the reserves against [[Newcastle Town F.C.|Newcastle Town]] at the end of September 2001, and then scored two more against [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C. Academy|Sheffield Wednesday]] on 1 November.<ref name=\"redstat\"/> Four days later, he made his senior debut in the [[EFL Cup|League Cup]] tie against [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] at [[Arsenal Stadium|Highbury]].<ref name=\"redstat\"/><ref name=\"debutarse\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/worthington_cup/1637817.stm |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306220908/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/worthington_cup/1637817.stm |archivedate=6 March 2016 |title=Arsenal win battle of reserves |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=5 November 2001 |accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref> He played the full game but United lost the [[2001\u201302 Football League Cup#Third round|third round]] match 4\u20130.<ref name=\"debutarse\"/> Back in the reserves, Davis continued to impress and scored four goals in six games between December and February 2002.<ref name=\"redstat\"/> He scored another hat-trick in the friendly against [[Drumchapel Amateur F.C.|Drumchapel Amateurs]] in March as United ran out 8\u22120 winners.<ref name=\"redstat\"/> Overall, he made 18 league appearances and scored six goals as United won the Premier Reserve League North.<ref name=\"redstat\"/>\n\n====Swindon Town (loan)====\nDavis joined [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]] club [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]] on a three-month loan deal in August 2002.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.swindontownfc.co.uk/today/view/breaking_news_detail/0,,10341~253023,00.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020818141949/http://www.swindontownfc.co.uk:80/today/view/breaking_news_detail/0,,10341~253023,00.html |archivedate=18 August 2002 |title=Jimmy Davis Signs Three-Month Contract |work=SwindonTownFC.co.uk |publisher=Swindon Town Football Club |date=9 August 2002 |accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref> On 10 August, he made his debut in the league game against [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]] when he replaced [[Danny Invincibile]] in the 84th minute of the 3\u22121 win.<ref name=\"season0203\">{{soccerbase season|23849|2002|accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.swindontownfc.co.uk/stats/view/postmatch_analysis/0,,10341~253510,00.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020818142232/http://www.swindontownfc.co.uk:80/stats/view/postmatch_analysis/0,,10341~253510,00.html |archivedate=18 August 2002 |title=Swindon Town 3 Barnsley 1 |work=SwindonTownFC.co.uk |publisher=Swindon Town Football Club |date=10 August 2002 |accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref> A week later he made his full debut in the goalless draw with [[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]] at [[Bloomfield Road]].<ref name=\"season0203\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.swindontownfc.co.uk/stats/view/postmatch_analysis/0,,10341~257798,00.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020822134048/http://www.swindontownfc.co.uk:80/stats/view/postmatch_analysis/0,,10341~257798,00.html |archivedate=22 August 2002 |title=Blackpool 0 Swindon Town 0 |work=SwindonTownFC.co.uk |publisher=Swindon Town Football Club |date=17 August 2002 |accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref> He scored his first goal for Swindon in the defeat against [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]] at the end of August.<ref name=\"season0203\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_2/2199507.stm |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040509141540/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_2/2199507.stm |archivedate=9 May 2004 |title=Brentford 3\u22121 Swindon |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=26 August 2002 |accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref> On 22 October, Davis scored in the [[EFL Trophy|Football League Trophy]] tie against [[Southend United F.C.|Southend United]]; he beat three players on the edge of the area before scoring as Town went on to win 6\u22121 in the [[2002\u201303 Football League Trophy#First round|first round]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/2344845.stm |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200201142808/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/2344845.stm |archivedate=1 February 2020 |title=Swindon 6\u22121 Southend |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=22 October 2002 |accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref> He scored again on 2 November against [[Wycombe Wanderers F.C.|Wycombe Wanderers]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_2/2363985.stm |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040523212155/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_2/2363985.stm |archivedate=23 May 2004 |title=Wycombe 2\u22123 Southend |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=2 November 2002 |accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref> and a week later he played in the 1\u22121 draw against [[Tranmere Rovers F.C.|Tranmere Rovers]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_2/2388065.stm |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040712025451/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_2/2388065.stm |archivedate=12 July 2004 |title=Swindon 1\u22121 Tranmere |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=9 November 2002 |accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref> the latter being his final appearance for Swindon.<ref name=\"season0203\"/> Town manager [[Andy King (footballer, born 1956)|Andy King]] was keen to keep Davis on loan at the club but United manager [[Alex Ferguson]] refused to extend the deal and Davis returned to Old Trafford following the Tranmere game.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.gazetteandherald.co.uk/news/7334954.jims-a-goner/ |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200421115151/https://www.gazetteandherald.co.uk/news/7334954.jims-a-goner/ |archivedate=21 April 2020 |title=Jim's a Goner |work=Gazette & Herald |publisher=Newsquest Media Group Ltd |date=8 November 2002 |accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref> Overall, he made 15 appearances for Swindon and scored three goals.<ref name=\"season0203\"/>\n\nUpon returning to United he was involved in the first team when he was an unused substitute in the [[Premier League]] match at [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] on 17 November.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/2430783.stm |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160319203642/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/eng_prem/2430783.stm |archivedate=19 March 2016 |title=Defoe denies Man Utd |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=17 November 2002 |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> He was again an unused substitute in their [[UEFA Champions League]] second group stage match away to [[Deportivo La Coruna]] on 18 March 2003.<ref>{{cite news |title=Deportivo see off Man Utd |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/champions_league/2856429.stm |website=BBC Sport |date=18 March 2003 |accessdate=20 April 2020 }}</ref> He joined [[Watford F.C.|Watford]] on a season-long loan on 8 July 2003.<ref>{{cite news |title=Watford lure Man Utd fledgling |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/w/watford/3054232.stm |website=BBC Sport |date=8 July 2003 |accessdate=20 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\n==International career==\n===Under-16===\nDavis represented [[England national under-16 football team|England]] at the [[1999 UEFA European Under-16 Championship]]. On 2 May 1999, he featured in the quarter final defeat against host nation [[Czech Republic national under-17 football team|Czech Republic]]; he replaced [[Jamie McMaster]] in the 86th minute as England lost 1\u22120 [[Overtime (sports)#Association football|after extra time]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://nv.fotbal.cz/en-national-teams/national-team-u-16/statistics/viewstat2.asp?page=/nat/16/1998/match15.asp |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180722011401/http://nv.fotbal.cz/en-national-teams/national-team-u-16/statistics/viewstat2.asp?page=/nat/16/1998/match15.asp |archivedate=22 July 2018 |title=Z\u00e1pis o utk\u00e1n\u00ed \u010d. 86 |work=Fotbal.cz |publisher=Fotbalov\u00e9 asociace \u010cesk\u00e9 republiky |language=Czech |date=2 May 1999 |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Under-18===\nDavis played for the [[England national under-18 football team|England under-18s]] in the win against [[Belgium national under-18 football team|Belgium]] in November 2000.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.dorsetecho.co.uk/news/5407330.defoe-given-half-a-game/ |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420123850/https://www.dorsetecho.co.uk/news/5407330.defoe-given-half-a-game/ |archivedate=20 April 2020 |title=Defoe given half a game |first= |last= |work=Dorset Echo |publisher=Newsquest Media Group Ltd |date=18 November 2000 |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Under-20===\nDavis made his debut for the [[England national under-20 football team|England under-20s]] in November 2001; he started the win against [[Portugal national under-20 football team|Portugal]] at [[St Mary's Stadium]] before being replaced by [[Andrew Johnson (footballer, born 1981)|Andrew Johnson]].<ref name=\"engonline\">{{cite web|url=http://www.englandfootballonline.com/MatchRsl/MatchRslTmU20.html |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229151245/http://www.englandfootballonline.com/MatchRsl/MatchRslTmU20.html |archivedate=29 February 2020 |title=England's Matches the under 20's |work=EnglandFootballOnline.com |publisher=England Football Online \u2212 Chris Goodwin & Glen Isherwood |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> On 13 March 2002, he scored two goals in the win against [[Finland national under-20 football team|Finland]] at the [[University of Bolton Stadium|Reebok Stadium]].<ref name=\"engonline\"/> He was a part of the squad that participated in the [[Toulon Tournament]] in May 2002;<ref name=\"espoirs\">{{cite web|url=https://festival-foot-espoirs.com/festival/archives/palmares.php?annee=2002 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190914203846/https://festival-foot-espoirs.com/festival/archives/palmares.php?annee=2002 |archivedate=14 September 2019 |title=30\u00c8 Festival International Espoirs |work=Festival-Foot-Espoirs.com |publisher=Festival International Espoirs |language=French |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> he featured in four games, scoring the winning goal in the group game against Portugal,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thefa.com/England/U20s/NewsAndFeatures/Postings/2002/05/11456.htm |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040313204835/http://www.thefa.com:80/England/U20s/NewsAndFeatures/Postings/2002/05/11456.htm |archivedate=13 March 2004 |title=Toulon: Davis on cue to seal victory |first=Lawrie |last=Madden |work=TheFA.com |publisher=The Football Association |date=13 May 2002 |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> as England finished in fourth place.<ref name=\"engonline\"/><ref name=\"espoirs\"/> He received the \"Le joueur le + courtois\" award, translated as being the most courteous player in the tournament.<ref name=\"espoirs\"/> These were his last appearances for the U20s. Overall, Davis earned seven caps and scored three goals.<ref name=\"engonline\"/>\n\n==Death==\nDavis was killed in a car crash on the [[M40 motorway]] in the early hours of 9 August 2003. He crashed his [[BMW]] into a truck and was pronounced dead at the scene. The truck driver suffered minor injuries. The accident occurred just hours before Watford were due to open their season with a match against [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]]. The Watford board of directors announced later that morning that the match was postponed due to \"tragic circumstances beyond their control\", though they did not announce Davis' death for another few hours. His funeral took place at Redditch Crematorium, with the Manchester United team in attendance.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.sky.com/skynews/article/0,,30100-12740453,00.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20110522070822/http://news.sky.com/skynews/article/0,,30100-12740453,00.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=22 May 2011 |title=Stars Pay Respect To Jimmy Davis |publisher=[[Sky News]] |date=23 August 2003 |accessdate=11 February 2008 }}</ref>\n\nThe subsequent [[inquest]] reported that Davis was more than twice over the legal drink-drive limit and it was believed that he had been driving at speeds of up to 120&nbsp;mph when losing control of his car when he fell asleep at the wheel.<ref name=\"inquest\">{{cite news | url=http://www.manchesteronline.co.uk/news/s/83/83016_crash_death_footballer_twice_drink_drive_limit.html | title=Crash death footballer twice drink drive limit | publisher=[[Manchester Evening News]] | date=3 March 2004 | accessdate=1 July 2007}}</ref> The inquest returned a verdict of accidental death.<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/manchester/3529553.stm | title=Under-21 United star over limit | work=BBC News | date=3 March 2004 | accessdate=6 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nA few days after his death, Swindon dedicated their 4\u20130 win over [[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]] to the young player, with Davis's mother making a speech in front of the Swindon fans before the kick-off. Additionally, Swindon Town took part in a memorial match with his local club [[Redditch United F.C.|Redditch United]]; Swindon won 2\u20131 with [[Sam Parkin]] scoring the goals. Manchester United paid tribute to him during their [[2003 FA Community Shield]] victory against [[Arsenal FC|Arsenal]], with both teams wearing black armbands during the match. United also paid tribute to him after their victory in the [[2004 FA Cup Final]], when after the final whistle and before the presentation they changed into shirts printed with Davis's name and squad number, 36, on the back.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/fa_cup/3739335.stm | title=Players remember Davis | publisher=[[BBC]] | date=22 May 2004 | accessdate=1 July 2007}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n;Specific\n{{reflist}}\n\n;General\n*[https://www.theguardian.com/football/2013/aug/05/jimmy-davis-danny-webber-united-watford \"'Jimmy was dead, when as far as I was concerned, he was still in bed'\"], ''[[The Guardian]]'', 5 August 2013\n\n==External links==\n* {{soccerbase}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20051207155002/http://www.manutd.com/bio/bio.sps?iBiographyID=1636 Jimmy Davis] at ManUtd.com\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Davis, Jimmy}}\n[[Category:1982 births]]\n[[Category:2003 deaths]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Bromsgrove]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football wingers]]\n[[Category:Manchester United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Royal Antwerp F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Swindon Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Watford F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Belgian First Division A players]]\n[[Category:English expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Belgium]]\n[[Category:Road incident deaths in England]]\n", "name_user": "Starvinho", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eManchester United", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jimmy_Davis_(footballer)"}
{"title_page": "Khan Academy", "text_new": "{{short description|Non-profit educational organization}}\n{{Infobox website\n| name              = Khan Academy\n| full_name         = NAMETSO PEARL MADIKWE\n| native_name       = THABISO TSHENOLO TSEEKU\n| native_name_lang  = NAMETSO THABISO\n| logo              = Khan Academy logo (2018).svg\n| logo_size         = 2\n| logo_alt          = 2\n| logo_caption      = 2\n| image             = 2\n| image_size        = 2\n| alt               = 2\n| caption           = HAPPY IN LIFE\n| alexa             = {{DecreasePositive}} 359 (April 2020)<ref name=\"alexa\">{{cite web |title=Khan Academy Traffic, Demographics and Competitors |url=https://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/khanacademy.org |website=www.alexa.com |accessdate=2020-04-11 |language=en}}</ref>\n| launch_date       = 2008\n| founder           = [[Sal Khan]]\n| founding_location = \n| extinction        = <!-- use {{end date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| merger            = \n| type              = [[501(c)(3) nonprofit organization|501(c)(3)]]\n| language          = English (primary)\n| owner             = <!-- or | owners = -->\n| website           = {{url|http://www.khanacademy.org}}\n}}\n'''Khan Academy''' is an American non-profit<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://projects.propublica.org/nonprofits/organizations/261544963 |title=Nonprofit Explorer \u2013 ProPublica |website=ProPublica |access-date=November 7, 2015}}</ref> educational organization created in 2008 by [[Sal Khan|Salman Khan]] with the goal of creating a set of online tools that help educate students.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/michaelnoer/2012/11/02/one-man-one-computer-10-million-students-how-khan-academy-is-reinventing-education/ |title=One Man, One Computer, 10 Million Students: How Khan Academy Is Reinventing Education |website=Forbes |access-date=November 7, 2015}}</ref> The organization produces short lessons in the form of videos.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Sampson |first=Demetrios G. |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=J5UpBAAAQBAJ |title=Digital Systems for Open Access to Formal and Informal Learning |last2=Ifenthaler |first2=Dirk |last3=Spector |first3=J. Michael |last4=Isaias |first4=Pedro |date=July 17, 2014 |publisher=Springer |isbn=9783319022642}}</ref> Its website also includes supplementary practice exercises and materials for educators. All resources are [[free education|available for free]] to users of the website and app. \n\nThe website and its content are provided mainly in [[English language|English]], but is also available in other languages including [[Arabic]], [[Armenian language|Armenian]], [[Azerbaijani language|Azerbaijani]], [[Bengali language|Bengali]], [[Bulgarian language|Bulgarian]], [[Chinese language|Chinese]], [[Czech language|Czech]], [[Danish language|Danish]], [[Dutch language|Dutch]], [[French language|French]], [[Georgian language|Georgian]], [[German language|German]], [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]], [[Hebrew language|Hebrew]], [[Hindi]], [[Indonesian language|Indonesian]], [[Italian language|Italian]], [[Japanese language|Japanese]], [[Korean language|Korean]], [[Norwegian language|Norwegian]], [[Polish language|Polish]], [[Portuguese language|Portuguese (Brazilian and European)]], [[Serbian language|Serbian]], [[Spanish language|Spanish]], [[Swedish language|Swedish]], [[Tamil language|Tamil]], [[Telugu language|Telugu]], [[Turkish language|Turkish]], [[Urdu]] and [[Uzbek language|Uzbek]].\n\n== History ==\n\nThe organization started in 2008 when Salman Khan tutored one of his cousins in mathematics on the Internet using a service called [[Yahoo!]] Doodle Images.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/education/educationnews/9568850/Khan-Academy-The-man-who-wants-to-teach-the-world.html |title=Khan Academy: The man who wants to teach the world |last=de Bertodano |first=Helena |date=September 28, 2012 |website=The Telegraph |access-date=September 27, 2018}}</ref> After a while, Khan's other cousins began to use his tutoring service. Due to the demand, Khan decided to make his videos watchable on the Internet, so he published his content on [[YouTube]].<ref name=\"Dreifus\">{{Cite news |last=Dreifus |first=Claudia |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/01/28/science/salman-khan-turned-family-tutoring-into-khan-academy.html |title=Salman Khan Turned Family Tutoring Into Khan Academy |date=January 27, 2014 |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=November 7, 2015 |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Later, he used a drawing application called SmoothDraw, and now uses a [[Wacom (company)|Wacom]] tablet to draw using [[ArtRage]]. The video tutorials were recorded on his computer.<ref>{{Cite AV media |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zxJgPHM5NYI&t=62s |title=Khan Academy: The future of education? |date=March 11, 2012 |publisher=[[CBS News]] |work=[[60 Minutes]] |via=[[YouTube]]}}</ref>\n\nThe positive responses prompted Khan to quit his job in 2009, and focus on the tutorials (then released under the name ''Khan Academy'') full-time.<ref name=\"sfgate\">{{Cite news |last=Temple |first=James |url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2009/12/13/BUKV1B11Q1.DTL |title=Salman Khan, math master of the Internet |date=December 14, 2009 |work=[[San Francisco Chronicle|SFgate]] |access-date=December 23, 2009}}</ref> [[Khan Lab School]], a school founded by Sal Khan and associated with Khan Academy, opened on September 15, 2014 in [[Mountain View, California]].<ref name=\"npr.org\">{{Cite news |last=Westervelt |first=Eric |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/ed/2016/01/05/461506508/sal-khan-on-learning-coding-and-why-virtual-ed-is-not-enough |title='A Bit of a Montessori 2.0': Khan Academy Opens A Lab School |date=January 5, 2016 |work=[[Here and Now (Boston)|Here & Now]] |access-date=January 6, 2016 |publisher=[[WBUR]] and [[NPR]]}}</ref> In June 2017, Khan Academy launched Financial Literacy Video Series for college graduates, job seekers and young professionals.\n\n==Funding ==\n\nKhan Academy is a [[501(c) organization#501(c)(3)|501(c)(3)]] [[nonprofit organization]], mostly funded by donations coming from philanthropic organizations.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.insidephilanthropy.com/home/2014/6/26/the-funders-pouring-money-into-the-khan-academy.html |title=The Funders Pouring Money Into the Khan Academy \u2013 Inside Philanthropy: Fundraising Intelligence \u2013 Inside Philanthropy |website=www.insidephilanthropy.com |access-date=November 7, 2015}}</ref> In 2010, [[Google]] donated $2 million for creating new courses and translating content into other languages, as part of their Project 10<sup>100</sup> program.<ref name=\"googleblog1\">{{Cite web |url=http://googleblog.blogspot.com/2010/09/10-million-for-project-10100-winners.html |title=$10 million for Project 10^100 winners |date=September 24, 2010 |publisher=The Official Google Blog |access-date=September 24, 2010}}</ref>  In 2013, [[Carlos Slim]] from the Carlos Slim Foundation in Mexico, made a donation for creating Spanish versions of videos.<ref name=\"carlosslim\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.marketplace.org/topics/life/education/mexicos-carlos-slim-funds-khan-academy-spanish |title=Mexico's Carlos Slim funds Khan academy in Spanish |publisher=Marketplace |access-date=2013-01-18 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150508202303/http://www.marketplace.org/topics/life/education/mexicos-carlos-slim-funds-khan-academy-spanish |archive-date=2015-05-08 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In 2015, [[AT&T]] contributed $2.25 million to Khan Academy for mobile versions of the content accessible through [[Mobile app|apps]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://philanthropynewsdigest.org/news/at-t-awards-2.25-million-for-mobile-learning-platform |title=AT&T Awards $2.25 Million for Mobile Learning Platform |website=Philanthropy News Digest (PND) |access-date=November 7, 2015}}</ref>  According to Khan Academy's filings with the U.S. [[Internal Revenue Service]], [[Sal Khan|Sal Khan's]] annual salary in 2015 was $800,000.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.guidestar.org/FinDocuments/2015/261/544/2015-261544963-0d2f1bbe-9.pdf |title=2015 Form 990 for Khan Academy |access-date=January 14, 2018}}</ref>  In 2013, former President and COO Shantanu Sinha also received over $375,000 in compensation.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://projects.propublica.org/nonprofits/organizations/261544963 |title=Nonprofit Explorer \u2013 KHAN ACADEMY INC \u2013 ProPublica' |publisher=[[ProPublica]] |access-date=September 22, 2015}}</ref> In 2018, Sal Khan's annual salary was $824,000. COO Ginny Lee's salary was $700,000.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://projects.propublica.org/nonprofits/organizations/261544963 |title=Nonprofit Explorer \u2013 KHAN ACADEMY INC \u2013 ProPublica' |publisher=[[ProPublica]] |access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Content ==\n\nKhan Academy's website aims to provide a personalized learning experience, mainly built on the videos which are hosted on [[YouTube]]. The website is meant to be used as a supplement to its videos, because it includes other features such as progress tracking, practice exercises,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,2397123,00.asp |title=Khan Academy |website=PCMAG |access-date=November 7, 2015}}</ref> and teaching tools.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://ww2.kqed.org/mindshift/2014/05/06/how-are-teachers-and-students-using-khan-academy/ |title=How Are Teachers and Students Using Khan Academy? |website=MindShift |access-date=November 7, 2015}}</ref> The material can also be accessed through mobile applications.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.theappzine.com/content/khan-academy-20-ipad |title=Khan Academy for ipad review |publisher=theappzine |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304094933/http://www.theappzine.com/content/khan-academy-20-ipad |archive-date=March 4, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe videos display a recording of drawings on an electronic blackboard, which are similar to the style of a teacher giving a lecture. The narrator describes each drawing and how they relate to the material being taught.<ref name=\"Gates favorite\">{{Cite news |last=Kaplan |first=David A. |url=http://money.cnn.com/2010/08/23/technology/sal_khan_academy.fortune/ |title=Innovation in Education: Bill Gates' favorite teacher |date=August 24, 2010 |work=CNN Money |access-date=January 5, 2011 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101223035558/http://money.cnn.com/2010/08/23/technology/sal_khan_academy.fortune/ |archive-date=December 23, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/education/2008-12-11-youtube-tutoring_N.htm |title=Need a tutor? YouTube videos await |date=December 12, 2008 |work=[[USA Today]] |access-date=January 5, 2011 |agency=AP}}</ref> Non-profit groups have distributed offline versions of the videos to rural areas in Asia, Latin America, and Africa.<ref name=\"Khan Academy\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.khanacademy.org/about#faq |title=A free world-class education for anyone anywhere |website=About |publisher=Khan academy |type=FAQ}}</ref><ref name=\"techawards1\">{{Cite web |url=http://thetechawards.thetech.org/the-laureates/salman-khan |title=Laureate: Salman Khan |year=2009 |website=Education Award |publisher=The Tech Awards |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140703085907/http://thetechawards.thetech.org/the-laureates/salman-khan |archive-date=July 3, 2014 |access-date=June 11, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cnbc.com/salman-khan/ |title=Salman Khan |website=CNBC |access-date=November 7, 2015}}</ref>  Videos range from all subjects covered in school and for all grades from kindergarten up through high school. The Khan Academy website also hosts content from educational YouTube channels and organizations such as [[Crash Course (YouTube)|Crash Course]] and the [[Museum of Modern Art]].<ref>[https://www.khanacademy.org/partner-content Khan Academy \u2013 Partner Content]</ref> It also provides online courses for preparing for standardized tests, including the [[SAT]] and [[Medical College Admission Test|MCAT]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.khanacademy.org/test-prep |title=Test prep &#124; Khan Academy |website=Khan Academy |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150420214602/https://www.khanacademy.org/test-prep |archive-date=April 20, 2015 |access-date=July 25, 2017}}</ref> and released LSAT preparation lessons in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.khanacademy.org/about/blog/post/174475327240/khan-academy-launches-free-official-lsat-prep |title=Khan Academy launches free Official LSAT Prep |date=June 1, 2018 |access-date=August 29, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2017, Khan Academy became the official practice partner for the [[Advanced Placement|College Board's Advanced Placement]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.khanacademy.org/about/blog/post/163503591115/khan-academy-is-the-official-practice-partner-for |title=Khan Academy is the Official Practice Partner for AP |date=July 27, 2017 |access-date=January 2, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Language availability ===\n\nKhan Academy videos have been translated into several languages, with close to 20,000 subtitle translations available. These translations are mainly volunteer-driven with help from international partnerships.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.khanacademy.org/contribute/credits |title=Volunteers &#124; Khan Academy |website=Khan Academy |language=en |access-date=March 6, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.khanacademy.org/about/our-supporters |title=Supporters &#124; Khan Academy |website=Khan Academy |language=en |access-date=March 6, 2017}}</ref> The Khan Academy platform is fully available in English (en), Bangla (bn), Bulgarian (bg), Chinese (zh), French (fr), German (de), Georgian (ka), Norwegian (nb), Polish (pl) Portuguese (pt), Spanish (es), Serbian (sr), Turkish (tr) and Uzbek (uz), and partially<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://khanacademy.zendesk.com/hc/en-us/articles/202483750-Is-Khan-Academy-available-in-other-languages- |title=Is Khan Academy available in other languages? |website=Khan Academy Help Center |language=en-US |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> available in 28 other languages.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://khanacademy.zendesk.com/hc/en-us/articles/202483750-Is-Khan-Academy-available-in-other-languages- |title=Is Khan Academy available in other languages? |website=Khan Academy Help Center |language=en-US |access-date=August 16, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Official SAT practicing ===\nSince 2015, Khan Academy has been the official [[SAT]] practicing website. According to reports, studying for the SAT for 20 hours on Khan Academy is associated with a 115-point average score increase.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.khanacademy.org/about/blog/post/160451329150/studying-for-the-sat-for-20-hours-on-khan-academy |title=Studying for the SAT for 20 hours on Khan Academy associated with 115-point average score increase |work=Khan Academy |access-date=September 8, 2018 |language=en}}</ref> Many book exercises select questions from the Khan Academy site to be published.{{cn|date=June 2019}}\n\n=== Pixar in a Box ===\nIn 2015, Khan Academy teamed up with [[Pixar]] to create a new course called Pixar in a Box, which teaches how skills learned in school help the creators at Pixar.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.khanacademy.org/partner-content/pixar |title=Pixar in a Box {{!}} Partner content {{!}} Khan Academy |website=Khan Academy |language=en |access-date=September 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Khan Academy Kids ===\nIn 2018, Khan Academy created an application called Khan Academy Kids. It is for young two-year-old to six-year-old children to learn basic skills before progressing to grade school.\n\n== Criticism ==\n\nKhan Academy has been criticized because its creator, Salman Khan, lacks a formal background or qualifications in [[pedagogy]].<ref name=\"how-well\">{{Cite news |last=Christopher Danielson |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/answer-sheet/post/how-well-does-khan-academy-teach/2012/07/27/gJQA9bWEAX_blog.html |title=How well does Khan Academy teach? |date=July 27, 2012 |work=The Washington Post |access-date=November 15, 2014 |last2=Michael Paul Goldenberg}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Strauss |first=Valerie |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/answer-sheet/post/how-well-does-khan-academy-teach/2012/07/27/gJQA9bWEAX_blog.html |title=Does the Khan Academy know how to teach? |date=July 27, 2012 |work=The Washington Post |access-date=November 7, 2015 |issn=0190-8286}}</ref> Statements made in several videos have been questioned for their technical accuracy, especially in the area of history.<ref name=\"using-contractors\" /> In response to these criticisms, the organization has corrected errors in its videos, expanded its faculty and formed a network of over 200 content experts.<ref name=\"using-contractors\">{{Cite news |last=Strauss, Valerie |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/answer-sheet/wp/2013/10/22/khan-academy-using-contractors-to-check-websites-videos/ |title=Khan Academy using contractors to check Web site's videos |date=October 22, 2013 |work=The Washington Post |access-date=November 15, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn an interview from January 2016, Khan defended the value of Khan Academy [[online lecture]]s while acknowledging their limitations: \"I think they're valuable, but I'd never say they somehow constitute a complete education.\"<ref name=\"npr.org\" /> Khan Academy positions itself as a supplement to in-class learning, with the ability to improve the effectiveness of teachers by freeing them from traditional lectures and giving them more time to tend to individual students' needs.<ref>{{Citation |last=Khan |first=Sal |title=Let's use video to reinvent education |url=https://www.ted.com/talks/salman_khan_let_s_use_video_to_reinvent_education |publisher=[[TED (conference)]] |language=en |access-date=March 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Recognition ==\n\nKhan Academy has gained recognition both nationally and internationally:\n* In April 2012, the founder and executive director of Khan Academy, [[Salman Khan (educator)|Salman Khan]], was listed among [[Time (magazine)|''TIME'''s]] 100 Most Influential People for 2012.<ref>{{Citation |title=Special |url=http://www.time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0,28804,2111975_2111976_2111942,00.html |publisher=Time}}.</ref>\n* Khan was one of five winners of the 2014 [[Heinz Award]]. His award was in the area of \"Human Condition.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.heinzawards.net/recipients/salman-khan |title=The Heinz Awards: Salman Khan |publisher=The Heinz Awards}}</ref>\n*In 2016, Khan Academy won a [[Shorty Awards|Shorty Award]] for Best in Education.<ref>{{Citation |title=Shorty Awards: The Complete Winners List |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/shorty-awards-2016-winners-full-882622 |publisher=- The Hollywood Reporter}}</ref>\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official|https://www.khanacademy.org/}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Commons category}}\n{{MOOC}}\n{{Princess of Asturias Award for International Cooperation}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:2008 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:501(c)(3) nonprofit organizations]]\n[[Category:Charities based in California]]\n[[Category:American educational websites]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:Educational organizations based in the United States]]\n[[Category:Education companies established in 2008]]\n[[Category:Educational technology non-profits]]\n[[Category:Education-related YouTube channels]]\n[[Category:Mountain View, California]]\n[[Category:Online nonprofit organizations]]\n[[Category:Open educational resources]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 2008]]\n[[Category:Online tutoring]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Non-profit educational organization}}\n{{Infobox website\n| name              = Khan Academy\n| full_name         = \n| native_name       = \n| native_name_lang  = \n| logo              = Khan Academy logo (2018).svg\n| logo_size         = \n| logo_alt          = \n| logo_caption      = \n| image             = \n| image_size        = \n| alt               = \n| caption           = \n| alexa             = {{DecreasePositive}} 359 (April 2020)<ref name=\"alexa\">{{cite web |title=Khan Academy Traffic, Demographics and Competitors |url=https://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/khanacademy.org |website=www.alexa.com |accessdate=2020-04-11 |language=en}}</ref>\n| launch_date       = 2008\n| founder           = [[Sal Khan]]\n| founding_location = \n| extinction        = <!-- use {{end date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| merger            = \n| type              = [[501(c)(3) nonprofit organization|501(c)(3)]]\n| language          = English (primary)\n| owner             = <!-- or | owners = -->\n| website           = {{url|http://www.khanacademy.org}}\n}}\n'''Khan Academy''' is an American non-profit<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://projects.propublica.org/nonprofits/organizations/261544963 |title=Nonprofit Explorer \u2013 ProPublica |website=ProPublica |access-date=November 7, 2015}}</ref> educational organization created in 2008 by [[Sal Khan|Salman Khan]] with the goal of creating a set of online tools that help educate students.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/michaelnoer/2012/11/02/one-man-one-computer-10-million-students-how-khan-academy-is-reinventing-education/ |title=One Man, One Computer, 10 Million Students: How Khan Academy Is Reinventing Education |website=Forbes |access-date=November 7, 2015}}</ref> The organization produces short lessons in the form of videos.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Sampson |first=Demetrios G. |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=J5UpBAAAQBAJ |title=Digital Systems for Open Access to Formal and Informal Learning |last2=Ifenthaler |first2=Dirk |last3=Spector |first3=J. Michael |last4=Isaias |first4=Pedro |date=July 17, 2014 |publisher=Springer |isbn=9783319022642}}</ref> Its website also includes supplementary practice exercises and materials for educators. All resources are [[free education|available for free]] to users of the website and app. \n\nThe website and its content are provided mainly in [[English language|English]], but is also available in other languages including [[Arabic]], [[Armenian language|Armenian]], [[Azerbaijani language|Azerbaijani]], [[Bengali language|Bengali]], [[Bulgarian language|Bulgarian]], [[Chinese language|Chinese]], [[Czech language|Czech]], [[Danish language|Danish]], [[Dutch language|Dutch]], [[French language|French]], [[Georgian language|Georgian]], [[German language|German]], [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]], [[Hebrew language|Hebrew]], [[Hindi]], [[Indonesian language|Indonesian]], [[Italian language|Italian]], [[Japanese language|Japanese]], [[Korean language|Korean]], [[Norwegian language|Norwegian]], [[Polish language|Polish]], [[Portuguese language|Portuguese (Brazilian and European)]], [[Serbian language|Serbian]], [[Spanish language|Spanish]], [[Swedish language|Swedish]], [[Tamil language|Tamil]], [[Telugu language|Telugu]], [[Turkish language|Turkish]], [[Urdu]] and [[Uzbek language|Uzbek]].\n\n== History ==\n\nThe organization started in 2008 when Salman Khan tutored one of his cousins in mathematics on the Internet using a service called [[Yahoo!]] Doodle Images.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/education/educationnews/9568850/Khan-Academy-The-man-who-wants-to-teach-the-world.html |title=Khan Academy: The man who wants to teach the world |last=de Bertodano |first=Helena |date=September 28, 2012 |website=The Telegraph |access-date=September 27, 2018}}</ref> After a while, Khan's other cousins began to use his tutoring service. Due to the demand, Khan decided to make his videos watchable on the Internet, so he published his content on [[YouTube]].<ref name=\"Dreifus\">{{Cite news |last=Dreifus |first=Claudia |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/01/28/science/salman-khan-turned-family-tutoring-into-khan-academy.html |title=Salman Khan Turned Family Tutoring Into Khan Academy |date=January 27, 2014 |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=November 7, 2015 |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Later, he used a drawing application called SmoothDraw, and now uses a [[Wacom (company)|Wacom]] tablet to draw using [[ArtRage]]. The video tutorials were recorded on his computer.<ref>{{Cite AV media |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zxJgPHM5NYI&t=62s |title=Khan Academy: The future of education? |date=March 11, 2012 |publisher=[[CBS News]] |work=[[60 Minutes]] |via=[[YouTube]]}}</ref>\n\nThe positive responses prompted Khan to quit his job in 2009, and focus on the tutorials (then released under the name ''Khan Academy'') full-time.<ref name=\"sfgate\">{{Cite news |last=Temple |first=James |url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2009/12/13/BUKV1B11Q1.DTL |title=Salman Khan, math master of the Internet |date=December 14, 2009 |work=[[San Francisco Chronicle|SFgate]] |access-date=December 23, 2009}}</ref> [[Khan Lab School]], a school founded by Sal Khan and associated with Khan Academy, opened on September 15, 2014 in [[Mountain View, California]].<ref name=\"npr.org\">{{Cite news |last=Westervelt |first=Eric |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/ed/2016/01/05/461506508/sal-khan-on-learning-coding-and-why-virtual-ed-is-not-enough |title='A Bit of a Montessori 2.0': Khan Academy Opens A Lab School |date=January 5, 2016 |work=[[Here and Now (Boston)|Here & Now]] |access-date=January 6, 2016 |publisher=[[WBUR]] and [[NPR]]}}</ref> In June 2017, Khan Academy launched Financial Literacy Video Series for college graduates, job seekers and young professionals.\n\n==Funding ==\n\nKhan Academy is a [[501(c) organization#501(c)(3)|501(c)(3)]] [[nonprofit organization]], mostly funded by donations coming from philanthropic organizations.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.insidephilanthropy.com/home/2014/6/26/the-funders-pouring-money-into-the-khan-academy.html |title=The Funders Pouring Money Into the Khan Academy \u2013 Inside Philanthropy: Fundraising Intelligence \u2013 Inside Philanthropy |website=www.insidephilanthropy.com |access-date=November 7, 2015}}</ref> In 2010, [[Google]] donated $2 million for creating new courses and translating content into other languages, as part of their Project 10<sup>100</sup> program.<ref name=\"googleblog1\">{{Cite web |url=http://googleblog.blogspot.com/2010/09/10-million-for-project-10100-winners.html |title=$10 million for Project 10^100 winners |date=September 24, 2010 |publisher=The Official Google Blog |access-date=September 24, 2010}}</ref>  In 2013, [[Carlos Slim]] from the Carlos Slim Foundation in Mexico, made a donation for creating Spanish versions of videos.<ref name=\"carlosslim\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.marketplace.org/topics/life/education/mexicos-carlos-slim-funds-khan-academy-spanish |title=Mexico's Carlos Slim funds Khan academy in Spanish |publisher=Marketplace |access-date=2013-01-18 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150508202303/http://www.marketplace.org/topics/life/education/mexicos-carlos-slim-funds-khan-academy-spanish |archive-date=2015-05-08 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In 2015, [[AT&T]] contributed $2.25 million to Khan Academy for mobile versions of the content accessible through [[Mobile app|apps]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://philanthropynewsdigest.org/news/at-t-awards-2.25-million-for-mobile-learning-platform |title=AT&T Awards $2.25 Million for Mobile Learning Platform |website=Philanthropy News Digest (PND) |access-date=November 7, 2015}}</ref>  According to Khan Academy's filings with the U.S. [[Internal Revenue Service]], [[Sal Khan|Sal Khan's]] annual salary in 2015 was $800,000.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.guidestar.org/FinDocuments/2015/261/544/2015-261544963-0d2f1bbe-9.pdf |title=2015 Form 990 for Khan Academy |access-date=January 14, 2018}}</ref>  In 2013, former President and COO Shantanu Sinha also received over $375,000 in compensation.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://projects.propublica.org/nonprofits/organizations/261544963 |title=Nonprofit Explorer \u2013 KHAN ACADEMY INC \u2013 ProPublica' |publisher=[[ProPublica]] |access-date=September 22, 2015}}</ref> In 2018, Sal Khan's annual salary was $824,000. COO Ginny Lee's salary was $700,000.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://projects.propublica.org/nonprofits/organizations/261544963 |title=Nonprofit Explorer \u2013 KHAN ACADEMY INC \u2013 ProPublica' |publisher=[[ProPublica]] |access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Content ==\n\nKhan Academy's website aims to provide a personalized learning experience, mainly built on the videos which are hosted on [[YouTube]]. The website is meant to be used as a supplement to its videos, because it includes other features such as progress tracking, practice exercises,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,2397123,00.asp |title=Khan Academy |website=PCMAG |access-date=November 7, 2015}}</ref> and teaching tools.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://ww2.kqed.org/mindshift/2014/05/06/how-are-teachers-and-students-using-khan-academy/ |title=How Are Teachers and Students Using Khan Academy? |website=MindShift |access-date=November 7, 2015}}</ref> The material can also be accessed through mobile applications.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.theappzine.com/content/khan-academy-20-ipad |title=Khan Academy for ipad review |publisher=theappzine |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304094933/http://www.theappzine.com/content/khan-academy-20-ipad |archive-date=March 4, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe videos display a recording of drawings on an electronic blackboard, which are similar to the style of a teacher giving a lecture. The narrator describes each drawing and how they relate to the material being taught.<ref name=\"Gates favorite\">{{Cite news |last=Kaplan |first=David A. |url=http://money.cnn.com/2010/08/23/technology/sal_khan_academy.fortune/ |title=Innovation in Education: Bill Gates' favorite teacher |date=August 24, 2010 |work=CNN Money |access-date=January 5, 2011 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101223035558/http://money.cnn.com/2010/08/23/technology/sal_khan_academy.fortune/ |archive-date=December 23, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/education/2008-12-11-youtube-tutoring_N.htm |title=Need a tutor? YouTube videos await |date=December 12, 2008 |work=[[USA Today]] |access-date=January 5, 2011 |agency=AP}}</ref> Non-profit groups have distributed offline versions of the videos to rural areas in Asia, Latin America, and Africa.<ref name=\"Khan Academy\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.khanacademy.org/about#faq |title=A free world-class education for anyone anywhere |website=About |publisher=Khan academy |type=FAQ}}</ref><ref name=\"techawards1\">{{Cite web |url=http://thetechawards.thetech.org/the-laureates/salman-khan |title=Laureate: Salman Khan |year=2009 |website=Education Award |publisher=The Tech Awards |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140703085907/http://thetechawards.thetech.org/the-laureates/salman-khan |archive-date=July 3, 2014 |access-date=June 11, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cnbc.com/salman-khan/ |title=Salman Khan |website=CNBC |access-date=November 7, 2015}}</ref>  Videos range from all subjects covered in school and for all grades from kindergarten up through high school. The Khan Academy website also hosts content from educational YouTube channels and organizations such as [[Crash Course (YouTube)|Crash Course]] and the [[Museum of Modern Art]].<ref>[https://www.khanacademy.org/partner-content Khan Academy \u2013 Partner Content]</ref> It also provides online courses for preparing for standardized tests, including the [[SAT]] and [[Medical College Admission Test|MCAT]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.khanacademy.org/test-prep |title=Test prep &#124; Khan Academy |website=Khan Academy |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150420214602/https://www.khanacademy.org/test-prep |archive-date=April 20, 2015 |access-date=July 25, 2017}}</ref> and released LSAT preparation lessons in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.khanacademy.org/about/blog/post/174475327240/khan-academy-launches-free-official-lsat-prep |title=Khan Academy launches free Official LSAT Prep |date=June 1, 2018 |access-date=August 29, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2017, Khan Academy became the official practice partner for the [[Advanced Placement|College Board's Advanced Placement]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.khanacademy.org/about/blog/post/163503591115/khan-academy-is-the-official-practice-partner-for |title=Khan Academy is the Official Practice Partner for AP |date=July 27, 2017 |access-date=January 2, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Language availability ===\n\nKhan Academy videos have been translated into several languages, with close to 20,000 subtitle translations available. These translations are mainly volunteer-driven with help from international partnerships.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.khanacademy.org/contribute/credits |title=Volunteers &#124; Khan Academy |website=Khan Academy |language=en |access-date=March 6, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.khanacademy.org/about/our-supporters |title=Supporters &#124; Khan Academy |website=Khan Academy |language=en |access-date=March 6, 2017}}</ref> The Khan Academy platform is fully available in English (en), Bangla (bn), Bulgarian (bg), Chinese (zh), French (fr), German (de), Georgian (ka), Norwegian (nb), Polish (pl) Portuguese (pt), Spanish (es), Serbian (sr), Turkish (tr) and Uzbek (uz), and partially<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://khanacademy.zendesk.com/hc/en-us/articles/202483750-Is-Khan-Academy-available-in-other-languages- |title=Is Khan Academy available in other languages? |website=Khan Academy Help Center |language=en-US |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> available in 28 other languages.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://khanacademy.zendesk.com/hc/en-us/articles/202483750-Is-Khan-Academy-available-in-other-languages- |title=Is Khan Academy available in other languages? |website=Khan Academy Help Center |language=en-US |access-date=August 16, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Official SAT practicing ===\nSince 2015, Khan Academy has been the official [[SAT]] practicing website. According to reports, studying for the SAT for 20 hours on Khan Academy is associated with a 115-point average score increase.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.khanacademy.org/about/blog/post/160451329150/studying-for-the-sat-for-20-hours-on-khan-academy |title=Studying for the SAT for 20 hours on Khan Academy associated with 115-point average score increase |work=Khan Academy |access-date=September 8, 2018 |language=en}}</ref> Many book exercises select questions from the Khan Academy site to be published.{{cn|date=June 2019}}\n\n=== Pixar in a Box ===\nIn 2015, Khan Academy teamed up with [[Pixar]] to create a new course called Pixar in a Box, which teaches how skills learned in school help the creators at Pixar.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.khanacademy.org/partner-content/pixar |title=Pixar in a Box {{!}} Partner content {{!}} Khan Academy |website=Khan Academy |language=en |access-date=September 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Khan Academy Kids ===\nIn 2018, Khan Academy created an application called Khan Academy Kids. It is for young two-year-old to six-year-old children to learn basic skills before progressing to grade school.\n\n== Criticism ==\n\nKhan Academy has been criticized because its creator, Salman Khan, lacks a formal background or qualifications in [[pedagogy]].<ref name=\"how-well\">{{Cite news |last=Christopher Danielson |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/answer-sheet/post/how-well-does-khan-academy-teach/2012/07/27/gJQA9bWEAX_blog.html |title=How well does Khan Academy teach? |date=July 27, 2012 |work=The Washington Post |access-date=November 15, 2014 |last2=Michael Paul Goldenberg}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Strauss |first=Valerie |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/answer-sheet/post/how-well-does-khan-academy-teach/2012/07/27/gJQA9bWEAX_blog.html |title=Does the Khan Academy know how to teach? |date=July 27, 2012 |work=The Washington Post |access-date=November 7, 2015 |issn=0190-8286}}</ref> Statements made in several videos have been questioned for their technical accuracy, especially in the area of history.<ref name=\"using-contractors\" /> In response to these criticisms, the organization has corrected errors in its videos, expanded its faculty and formed a network of over 200 content experts.<ref name=\"using-contractors\">{{Cite news |last=Strauss, Valerie |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/answer-sheet/wp/2013/10/22/khan-academy-using-contractors-to-check-websites-videos/ |title=Khan Academy using contractors to check Web site's videos |date=October 22, 2013 |work=The Washington Post |access-date=November 15, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn an interview from January 2016, Khan defended the value of Khan Academy [[online lecture]]s while acknowledging their limitations: \"I think they're valuable, but I'd never say they somehow constitute a complete education.\"<ref name=\"npr.org\" /> Khan Academy positions itself as a supplement to in-class learning, with the ability to improve the effectiveness of teachers by freeing them from traditional lectures and giving them more time to tend to individual students' needs.<ref>{{Citation |last=Khan |first=Sal |title=Let's use video to reinvent education |url=https://www.ted.com/talks/salman_khan_let_s_use_video_to_reinvent_education |publisher=[[TED (conference)]] |language=en |access-date=March 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Recognition ==\n\nKhan Academy has gained recognition both nationally and internationally:\n* In April 2012, the founder and executive director of Khan Academy, [[Salman Khan (educator)|Salman Khan]], was listed among [[Time (magazine)|''TIME'''s]] 100 Most Influential People for 2012.<ref>{{Citation |title=Special |url=http://www.time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0,28804,2111975_2111976_2111942,00.html |publisher=Time}}.</ref>\n* Khan was one of five winners of the 2014 [[Heinz Award]]. His award was in the area of \"Human Condition.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.heinzawards.net/recipients/salman-khan |title=The Heinz Awards: Salman Khan |publisher=The Heinz Awards}}</ref>\n*In 2016, Khan Academy won a [[Shorty Awards|Shorty Award]] for Best in Education.<ref>{{Citation |title=Shorty Awards: The Complete Winners List |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/shorty-awards-2016-winners-full-882622 |publisher=- The Hollywood Reporter}}</ref>\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official|https://www.khanacademy.org/}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Commons category}}\n{{MOOC}}\n{{Princess of Asturias Award for International Cooperation}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:2008 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:501(c)(3) nonprofit organizations]]\n[[Category:Charities based in California]]\n[[Category:American educational websites]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:Educational organizations based in the United States]]\n[[Category:Education companies established in 2008]]\n[[Category:Educational technology non-profits]]\n[[Category:Education-related YouTube channels]]\n[[Category:Mountain View, California]]\n[[Category:Online nonprofit organizations]]\n[[Category:Open educational resources]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 2008]]\n[[Category:Online tutoring]]\n", "name_user": "Thabiso aqute", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Khan_Academy"}
{"title_page": "History of Tirumala Venkateswara Temple", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=May 2019}}\n{{Main|Venkateswara Temple, Tirumala}}\n{{Hinduism small}}\n'''Venkateswara Temple''' is an important [[Vaishnavism|Vaishnavite]] temple situated in the hill town of [[Tirumala]] in [[Chittoor district]] of Andhra Pradesh, India. The Temple is dedicated to Lord [[Venkateswara]], an incarnation of [[Vishnu]], who is believed to be appeared here to save mankind from the trials and troubles of [[Kali Yuga]]. The temple is situated at a height of 853 metres on Tirumala Hills which are part of Seshachalam Hills and is constructed in Dravidian Architectural Style.\n\n==Medieval history==\nThe first recorded endowment was made by Pallava queen Samavai in the year 966 CE. She donated many jewels and two parcels of land (one 10 acres and other 13 acres) and ordered to use the revenues generated from that land to be used for the celebration of major festivals in the temple.{{sfn|Feminism and World Religions| 1999| p= 48}} The [[Pallava dynasty]] (9th century), the [[Chola dynasty]] (10th century), and Vijayanagara [[pradhan]]s (14th and 15th centuries) were committed devotees of Lord Venkateswara. The temple gained most of its current wealth and size under the [[Vijayanagara Empire]], with the donation of diamonds and gold.<ref name = 'Tirumalatemple'>{{cite book |author=Dr. N.Ramesan|title=The Tirumala Temple |year=1981 |publisher=Tirumala Tirupati Devasthanams|location=Tirumala}}</ref> In 1517, Vijayanagara Emperor [[Krishnadevaraya]], on one of his many visits to the temple, donated gold and jewels, enabling the [[Ananda Nilayam]] (inner shrine) roofing to be gilded. After the decline of Vijayanagara Empire, leaders from states such as the [[Kingdom of Mysore]] and the [[Gadwal Samsthanam]] worshiped as pilgrims and gave ornaments and valuables to the temple. Maratha general [[Raghoji I Bhonsle]] (died 1755) visited the temple and set up a permanent administration for the conduct of worship in the temple.{{Citation needed|date=August 2018}}<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.tirumala.org/maintemple_history.htm| title=Tirumala Tirupati Devasthanams: Temple History| accessdate=15 July 2011| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120412013703/http://www.tirumala.org/maintemple_history.htm| archive-date=12 April 2012| url-status=dead| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Modern history==\n\nAfter the dusk of [[Vijayanagara Empire]], the temple went into the hands of Golconda in July 1656 and then it was under the French  for a short period of time and under Nawab of Carnatic till 1801 CE.\n\n===During 15th Century===\nIn 1417 AD, Madhavadasar, a resident of chandragiri, constructed Tirumamani mandapam which is present in front of bangaru vakili of the garbhagriha.<ref name=cons1>{{cite book|title=Temples in and Around Tirupati|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rt3VAAAAMAAJ&q=krishnadevaraya+and+tirupati&dq=krishnadevaraya+and+tirupati&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjPzLK-wrDfAhUOOisKHWsaCUo4ChDoAQg-MAQ}}</ref>\n\n===During 16th Century===\nIn 1535 AD, Pedda Tirumalacharya renovated [[Architecture of Tirumala Venkateswara Temple#Pushkarni|Temple Tank]] and [[Varahaswamy Temple, Tirumala|Adivaraha shrine]].<ref name=cons1 />\n\n===During 19th Century===\nWith the advent of British during the early 19th century, the management of the temple passed to hands of [[East India Company]], who accorded special status to temple and avoided interference in temple activities.<ref name=british>{{cite book |last=V.K|first=Bhaskara Rao |title=Organisational and Financial Management of Religious Institutions: With Special Reference to Tirumala Tirupati Devasthanams (TTD) |publisher=Deep and Deep Publications |date=1992 |pages=52, 53|isbn=81-7100-441-5}}</ref> Madras government passed Regulation seven of 1817, which passed the temple to Board of Revenue through collector of North Arcot District.<ref name=british /> In 1821, Bruce of England had drawn rules for the management of Temple which is referred to as ''[[Bruce's Code]]''.<ref name=british />\n\nIn 1843 the [[East India Company]] transferred the Administration of Temple along with [[List of temples under Tirumala Tirupati Devasthanams#In Tirupati|other Temples in Tirupati]] to [[Mahant]]s of [[Hathiram Bhavaji#Hathiramji Muth|Hathiramji Muth]], who acted as Vicaranakartas.\n\n===During 20th Century===\nThe Temple was under the rule of Mahants for six generations until 1933 when [[Tirumala Tirupati Devasthanams]] was formed as a result of the TTD Act in 1933.<ref>{{cite book |last=Koutha |first=Nirmala Kumari |title=History of the Hindu Religious Endowments in Andhra Pradesh |publisher=Northern Book Centre |date=1 January 1998 |page=124 |isbn=81-7211-085-5}}</ref> The Act of 1933 was superseded by Madras Hindu Religious and Charitable Endowment Act of 1951.<ref name=apendowments>{{cite book |last=Koutha |first=Nirmala Kumari |title=History of the Hindu Religious Endowments in Andhra Pradesh |publisher=Northern Book Centre |date=1 January 1998 |page=136 |isbn=81-7211-085-5}}</ref> Again in  1966, the temple was placed under direct control of [[Andhra pradesh]] State Endowments Department, with Andhra Pradesh Charitable and Hindu Religious Institutions and Endowments act.<ref name=apendowments /> In 1979, act of 1966 was rolled back with new Tirumala Tirupati Devasthanams act, where temple administration was vested to a committee consisting of Executive officer, Chairman and two other members nominated by [[Government of Andhra Pradesh]].<ref name=apendowments />\n\n{{See also|Tirumala Tirupati Devasthanams#Establishment and legislative setting|l1=Establishment and legislative setting of TTD}}\n\n==Epigraphical records==\nThis Temple bears on its walls several inscriptions which are of historical, cultural and linguistic importance. The number of inscriptions on the Hill Temple and in the temples of Lower Tirupati and Tiruchanur exceed one thousand. There is evidence to suggest that many early inscriptions on the walls of the temples have disappeared beyond recovery. As many as 640 inscriptions are found engraved on the walls of the temple. They are published by the [[Tirumala Tirupati Devasthanams]] along with the inscriptions found in other related temples in and around Tirupati. All the inscriptions are in [[Kannada]], [[Sanskrit]], [[Tamil language|Tamil]], [[Telugu language|Telugu]] <ref>{{Cite web |url=http://srivenkatesa.org/index.php/temple/templehistory/675-tirumala-hill-shrine-and-inscriptions |title=Archived copy |access-date=22 October 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208115439/http://srivenkatesa.org/index.php/temple/templehistory/675-tirumala-hill-shrine-and-inscriptions |archive-date=8 December 2015 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nAdditionally, in the temple, there is a unique collection of about 3000 copper plates on which the [[Carnatic music|Telugu Sankirtanas]] of [[Tallapaka Annamacharya]] and his descendants are inscribed. This collection forms a valuable source of material for a historical linguist in Telugu apart from its importance to musicologists.{{citation needed|date=May 2019}}\n\nUnder the patronage of almost all important dynasties of South India, this sacred Temple of Tirumala enjoyed full benefits and glory. The [[Pallavas]], the [[Cholas]], the [[Pandyas]], [[Kadava]]rayas, Yadavarayas, [[Telugu Cholas]], Telugu Pallavas, Vijayanagara kings (Sangama, Saluva and Tuluva lines) have left the marks of their patronage and endowments on the walls of the temples of Tirumala and Tirupati.<ref name=\"tirumala.org\">{{cite web |url=http://www.tirumala.org/maintemple_main.htm |title=Tirumala Tirupati Devastanamulu |publisher=Tirumala.org |accessdate=17 June 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020806184716/http://www.tirumala.org/maintemple_main.htm |archive-date=6 August 2002 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Tirumala Venkateswara Temple]]\n[[Category:Tirupati]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=May 2019}}\n{{Main|Venkateswara Temple, Tirumala}}\n{{Hinduism small}}\n'''Venkateswara Temple''' is an important [[Vaishnavism|Vaishnavite]] temple situated in the hill town of [[Tirumala]] in [[Chittoor district]] of Andhra Pradesh, India. The Temple is dedicated to Lord [[Venkateswara]], an incarnation of [[Vishnu]], who is believed to be appeared here to save mankind from trails and troubles of [[Kali Yuga]]. The temple is situated at a height of 853 metres on Tirumala Hills which are part of Seshachalam Hills and is constructed in Dravidian Architectural Style. \n\n==Medieval history==\nThe first recorded endowment was made by Pallava queen Samavai in the year 966 CE. She donated many jewels and two parcels of land (one 10 acres and other 13 acres) and ordered to use the revenues generated from that land to be used for the celebration of major festivals in the temple.{{sfn|Feminism and World Religions| 1999| p= 48}} The [[Pallava dynasty]] (9th century), the [[Chola dynasty]] (10th century), and Vijayanagara [[pradhan]]s (14th and 15th centuries) were committed devotees of Lord Venkateswara. The temple gained most of its current wealth and size under the [[Vijayanagara Empire]], with the donation of diamonds and gold.<ref name = 'Tirumalatemple'>{{cite book |author=Dr. N.Ramesan|title=The Tirumala Temple |year=1981 |publisher=Tirumala Tirupati Devasthanams|location=Tirumala}}</ref> In 1517, Vijayanagara Emperor [[Krishnadevaraya]], on one of his many visits to the temple, donated gold and jewels, enabling the [[Ananda Nilayam]] (inner shrine) roofing to be gilded. After the decline of Vijayanagara Empire, leaders from states such as the [[Kingdom of Mysore]] and the [[Gadwal Samsthanam]] worshiped as pilgrims and gave ornaments and valuables to the temple. Maratha general [[Raghoji I Bhonsle]] (died 1755) visited the temple and set up a permanent administration for the conduct of worship in the temple.{{Citation needed|date=August 2018}}<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.tirumala.org/maintemple_history.htm| title=Tirumala Tirupati Devasthanams: Temple History| accessdate=15 July 2011| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120412013703/http://www.tirumala.org/maintemple_history.htm| archive-date=12 April 2012| url-status=dead| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Modern history==\n\n\n\nAfter the dusk of [[Vijayanagara Empire]], the temple went into the hands of Golconda in July 1656 and then it was under the French  for a short period of time and under Nawab of Carnatic till 1801 CE. \n\n===During 15th Century===\nIn 1417 AD, Madhavadasar, a resident of chandragiri, constructed Tirumamani mandapam which is present infront of bangaru vakili of the garbhagriha.<ref name=cons1>{{cite book|title=Temples in and Around Tirupati|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rt3VAAAAMAAJ&q=krishnadevaraya+and+tirupati&dq=krishnadevaraya+and+tirupati&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjPzLK-wrDfAhUOOisKHWsaCUo4ChDoAQg-MAQ}}</ref>\n===During 16th Century===\nIn 1535 AD, Pedda Tirumalacharya renovated [[Architecture_of_Tirumala_Venkateswara_Temple#Pushkarni|Temple Tank]] and [[Varahaswamy Temple, Tirumala|Adivaraha shrine]]. <ref name=cons1 />\n===During 19th Century===\nWith the advent of British during the early 19th century, the management of the temple passed to hands of [[East India Company]], who accorded special status to temple and avoided interference in temple activities.<ref name=british>{{cite book |last=V.K|first=Bhaskara Rao |title=Organisational and Financial Management of Religious Institutions: With Special Reference to Tirumala Tirupati Devasthanams (TTD) |publisher=Deep and Deep Publications |date=1992 |page=52, 53|isbn=81-7100-441-5}}</ref> Madras government passed Regulation seven of 1817, which passed the temple to Board of Revenue through collector of North Arcot District.<ref name=british /> In 1821, Bruce of England had drawn rules for the management of Temple which is referred to as ''[[Bruce's Code]]''.<ref name=british />\n\nIn 1843 the [[East India Company]] transferred the Administration of Temple along with [[List of temples under Tirumala Tirupati Devasthanams#In Tirupati|other Temples in Tirupati]] to [[Mahant]]s of [[Hathiram Bhavaji#Hathiramji Muth|Hathiramji Muth]], who acted as Vicaranakartas. \n\n===During 20th Century===\nThe Temple was under the rule of Mahants for six generations until 1933 when [[Tirumala Tirupati Devasthanams]] was formed as a result of the TTD Act in 1933.<ref>{{cite book |last=Koutha |first=Nirmala Kumari |title=History of the Hindu Religious Endowments in Andhra Pradesh |publisher=Northern Book Centre |date=1 January 1998 |page=124 |isbn=81-7211-085-5}}</ref> The Act of 1933 was superseded by Madras Hindu Religious and Charitable Endowment Act of 1951.<ref name=apendowments>{{cite book |last=Koutha |first=Nirmala Kumari |title=History of the Hindu Religious Endowments in Andhra Pradesh |publisher=Northern Book Centre |date=1 January 1998 |page=136 |isbn=81-7211-085-5}}</ref> Again in  1966, the temple was placed under direct control of [[Andhra pradesh]] State Endowments Department, with Andhra Pradesh Charitable and Hindu Religious Institutions and Endowments act.<ref name=apendowments /> In 1979, act of 1966 was rolled back with new Tirumala Tirupati Devasthanams act, where temple administration was vested to a committee consisting of Executive officer, Chairman and two other members nominated by [[Government of Andhra Pradesh]].<ref name=apendowments />\n\n{{See also|Tirumala Tirupati Devasthanams#Establishment and legislative setting|l1=Establishment and legislative setting of TTD}}\n\n==Epigraphical records==\nThis Temple bears on its walls several inscriptions which are of historical, cultural and linguistic importance. The number of inscriptions on the Hill Temple and in the temples of Lower Tirupati and Tiruchanur exceed one thousand. There is evidence to suggest that many early inscriptions on the walls of the temples have disappeared beyond recovery. As many as 640 inscriptions are found engraved on the walls of the temple. They are published by the [[Tirumala Tirupati Devasthanams]] along with the inscriptions found in other related temples in and around Tirupati. All the inscriptions are in [[Kannada]], [[Sanskrit]], [[Tamil language|Tamil]], [[Telugu language|Telugu]] <ref>{{Cite web |url=http://srivenkatesa.org/index.php/temple/templehistory/675-tirumala-hill-shrine-and-inscriptions |title=Archived copy |access-date=22 October 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208115439/http://srivenkatesa.org/index.php/temple/templehistory/675-tirumala-hill-shrine-and-inscriptions |archive-date=8 December 2015 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nAdditionally, in the temple, there is a unique collection of about 3000 copper plates on which the [[Carnatic music|Telugu Sankirtanas]] of [[Tallapaka Annamacharya]] and his descendants are inscribed. This collection forms a valuable source of material for a historical linguist in Telugu apart from its importance to musicologists.{{fact|date=May 2019}}\n\nUnder the patronage of almost all important dynasties of South India, this sacred Temple of Tirumala enjoyed full benefits and glory. The [[Pallavas]], the [[Cholas]], the [[Pandyas]], [[Kadava]]rayas, Yadavarayas, [[Telugu Cholas]], Telugu Pallavas, Vijayanagara kings (Sangama, Saluva and Tuluva lines) have left the marks of their patronage and endowments on the walls of the temples of Tirumala and Tirupati.<ref name=\"tirumala.org\">{{cite web |url=http://www.tirumala.org/maintemple_main.htm |title=Tirumala Tirupati Devastanamulu |publisher=Tirumala.org |accessdate=17 June 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020806184716/http://www.tirumala.org/maintemple_main.htm |archive-date=6 August 2002 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Tirumala Venkateswara Temple]]\n[[Category:Tirupati]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "Typo/generalfixes, replaced: infront \u2192 in front, trails and troubles \u2192 trials and troubles", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_Tirumala_Venkateswara_Temple"}
{"title_page": "Jan Ga\u0142\u0105zka", "text_new": "{{short description|Polish boxer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name           = Jan Ga\u0142\u0105zka\n| full_name      = \n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| nationality    = Polish\n| sport          = [[Boxing]]\n| birth_date     = {{birth date|1945|2|4|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = [[Bia\u0142ystok]], Poland\n| death_date     = {{death date and age|1982|1|7|1945|2|4|df=yes}}\n| death_place    = Bia\u0142ystok, Poland\n| medaltemplates = \n{{MedalSport|Men's [[amateur boxing]]}}\n{{MedalCountry|{{POL}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[European Amateur Boxing Championships|European  Amateur Championships]]}}\n{{MedalSilver| [[1965 European Amateur Boxing Championships|1965 East Berlin]] | Bantamweight}}\n}}\n\n'''Jan Ga\u0142\u0105zka''' (4 January 1945 &ndash; 7 January 1982) was a Polish [[boxing|boxer]]. He competed in the [[Boxing at the 1968 Summer Olympics \u2013 Bantamweight|men's bantamweight]] event at the [[1968 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"SportsRef\">{{cite Sports-Reference |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ga/jan-galazka-1.html |title=Jan Ga\u0142\u0105zka Olympic Results |accessdate=8 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==1968 Olympic results==\nBelow is the record of Jan Ga\u0142\u0105zka, a Polish bantamweight boxer who competed at the 1968 Mexico City Olympics:\n\n* Round of 64: bye\n* Round of 32: lost to Roberto Cervantes (Mexico) by decision, 0-5\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Galazka, Jan}}\n[[Category:1945 births]]\n[[Category:1982 deaths]]\n[[Category:Polish male boxers]]\n[[Category:Olympic boxers of Poland]]\n[[Category:Boxers at the 1968 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Bia\u0142ystok]]\n{{Poland-boxing-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Polish boxer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name           = Jan Ga\u0142\u0105zka\n| full_name      = \n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| nationality    = Polish\n| sport          = [[Boxing]]\n| birth_date     = {{birth date|1945|2|4|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = [[Bia\u0142ystok]], Poland\n| death_date     = {{death date and age|1982|1|7|1945|2|4|df=yes}}\n| death_place    = Bia\u0142ystok, Poland\n| medaltemplates = \n{{MedalSport|Men's [[amateur boxing]]}}\n{{MedalCountry|{{POL}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[European Amateur Boxing Championships|European  Amateur Championships]]}}\n{{MedalSilver| [[1965 European Amateur Boxing Championships|1965 East Berlin]] | Bantamweight}}\n}}\n\n'''Jan Ga\u0142\u0105zka''' (4 January 1945 &ndash; 7 January 1982) was a Polish [[boxing|boxer]]. He competed in the [[Boxing at the 1968 Summer Olympics \u2013 Bantamweight|men's bantamweight]] event at the [[1968 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"SportsRef\">{{cite Sports-Reference |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ga/jan-galazka-1.html |title=Jan Ga\u0142\u0105zka Olympic Results |accessdate=8 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==1968 Olympic results==\nBelow is the record of Jan Ga\u0142\u0105zka, a Polish bantamweigth boxer who competed at the 1968 Mexico City Olympics:\n\n* Round of 64: bye\n* Round of 32: lost to Roberto Cervantes (Mexico) by decision, 0-5\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Galazka, Jan}}\n[[Category:1945 births]]\n[[Category:1982 deaths]]\n[[Category:Polish male boxers]]\n[[Category:Olympic boxers of Poland]]\n[[Category:Boxers at the 1968 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Bia\u0142ystok]]\n{{Poland-boxing-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Worldlywise", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e1968 Olympic results", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jan_Ga%C5%82%C4%85zka"}
